<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Sending Envoy to Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The White House on Monday
denied a report that the Clinton administration had sent a special
envoy to Tehran looking possible changes in Iranian foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
"We have no plans to send a special envoy to Tehran at all,"
White House spokesman Eric Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The report came from the official news agency of the United
Arab Emirates, which said in a Washington-datelined dispatch that
President Bill Clinton had sent Tom Lantos, a Congressman of
California Democrat, to Tehran in an effort to find any evidence
for the changes of Iranian foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the reported visit by Lantos was "news to us."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Latos' office at the Capitol Hill made no
immediate answer to any call asking the Congressman's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States was looking for "deeds not words"
to confirm any changes in Iranian foreign policy since Mohammad
Khatami was elected the Iranian president in the May elections.
</P>
<P>
Khatami expressed his hope to restore dialogue with the United
States at a news conference in Tehran on Dec. 14 and Clinton
responded two days later with a positive tone for that proposal.
</P>
<P>
"I think it was sa tragic that the United States was separated
from the people of Iran," Clinton said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed the U.S. position for the possible dialogue,
saying three issues should be discussed before any dialogue could
be considered.
</P>
<P>
The three allegations include: Iran's support and funding for
terrorism, opposition to the U.S.-sponsored Middle East peace
process and its development of weapons of mass destruction, all
of which the Iranian government has flatly denied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
