<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Women at Work Now Outnumber Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 29 (Xinhua) - British women outnumber men in
the workplace for the first time in peacetime history, official
figures show.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Office for National Statistics reveal there
are 12000 more women than men in paid employment. There are a
total of 11248000 women in work compared to 11236000 men.
</P>
<P>
Partly as a result of this increase, the Government is ready to
launch a campaign to persuade employers to become more "family
friendly".
</P>
<P>
It is reported that companies have not changed their practices
enough to reflect the huge expansion in the number of women in the
workforce.
</P>
<P>
A committee of eight ministers chaired by Home Secretary Jack
Straw is drawing up proposals to make life at work easier for
women.
</P>
<P>
It urges firms to provide creches and nursery vouchers and make
it easier for parents to job-share and work part-time.
</P>
<P>
A report published today by the Policy Studies Institute claims
that women are still being discriminated against in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
It says they receive less pay and training than men, and that
employers are less likely to use women's experience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
