<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Pledges Not to Resume Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cape Town, December 29 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela reiterated today that his government would
establish diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of
China in late 1997 and never resume official ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qichen here, Mandela said diplomatic ties
between South Africa and Taiwan would never be resumed after the
normalization of Pretoria-Beijing relations due to be realized as
of January 1.
</P>
<P>
Mandela announced in November last year that his government
would sever diplomatic ties with Taiwan and establish
comprehensive relations with the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the reason of setting up diplomatic relations
with China, Mandela said that China, a permanent member in the
United Nations Security Council, is one of the most populous
states in the world where economy is developing very fast.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the interest of South Africa to have diplomatic ties
with the People's Republic of China," Mandela noted, adding his
government will uphold "one-China policy".
</P>
<P>
In response, Qian firstly relay greetings from Chinese
President Jiang Zemin who invited Mandela to visit China at his
convenience while Mandela also asked Qian to convey his best
regards to Jiang and invited him to visit South Africa as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, Qian said the forthcoming
normalization of Sino-South African relations is not only a big
event in the history of the two countries, but also conducive to
world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The peoples of the two countries will be very happy about
this, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed out that there is great potentiality in economic
exchange and trade between China and South Africa, saying that
China is willing to make positive contribution to the development
of South African economy.
</P>
<P>
Qian arrived in South Africa Sunday for a five-day official
visit at the invitation of his South African counterpart Alfred
Nzo. The two ministers will meet Tuesday over bilateral relations
and sign a joint communique on the establishment of official
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian will attend the opening ceremony of the Chinese embassy
in Pretoria, the capital of South Africa on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his meeting with Mandela, Qian also had friendly
talks with Premier of Gauteng Province Tokyo Sexwale, with the
two sides pledging to continue promoting cooperation in various
fields.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Qian's visit are his wife Zhou Hanqiong, Deputy
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng
and Assistant Foreign Minister Ji Peiding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
