<HEADLINE> 609 Killed on S. African Roads in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A total of 609 people
have been killed in traffic accidents this month, South African
traffic authorities said today.
</P>
<P>
This was nearly half the road deaths between December 3, 1996
and January 12, 1997, the "Arrive Alive" campaign was quoted by
South African Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
Six people died this morning in a head-on collision between a
bus and a mini-bus taxi near Carltonville, which is 75 kilometers
southwest of Johannesburg, the campaign said.
</P>
<P>
The taxi was burnt out and all its occupants were killed,
while no one in the bus was injured, it said.
</P>
<P>
The top three provinces on this month's road death toll list
are Eastern Cape, at 109, Kwazulu-Natal, where Durban seaport is
located, at 106, and Gauteng, centered around Pretoria and
Johannesburg, at 98.
</P>
<P>
The campaign attributed the accidents mainly to speeding,
driver fatigue and pedestrian jaywalking.
</P>
<P>
Traffic volumes on most of the country's major roads were
normal today, but were expected to pick up from Friday, when most
people return from their holidays, the campaign said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign's traffic information center said today that law
enforcement would be tightened on roads nationwide around New
Year's Day, including setting up road blocks testing drinking and
seat-belt using.
</P>
<P>
"In particular there will be numerous road blocks testing for
motorists driving under the influence of alcohol from December
31, 1997 to January 1, 1998," the center said, warning that road
offenders would stand a high probability of being prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Gauteng, Kwazulu-Natal and the Western Cape would be targeted
because three quarters of road accidents and 53 percent of
fatalities were recorded there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
