<HEADLINE> Bulgaria To Remove Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Starting from January 1, 1998,
Bulgaria will implement a new policy to remove trade barriers by
encouraging exports of Bulgarian products and imports of foreign
products with high added-value.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Bulgarian Minister of Trade and Tourism
Valentin Vasilev Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the new policy will exempt types of
agricultural machineries, mining machineries, coal, and cultural
items such as musical instruments and movies from import
taxes. The import tax on vegetable oil will be reduced 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
To encourage export, he said, agricultural products such as
grains and feeds will become tax free, and taxes on 26 types of
important materials including livestocks and timber will be cut by
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vasilev added the new policy was made in line with the
requirements of the European Union, World Trade Organization,
International Monetary Fund, and World Bank, so as to help open
Bulgaria, a country with formidable trade barriers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
