<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Warns Firms to Act Fast on Millennium Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 29 (Xinhua) - Organizations which fail to take
action to change their computers to cope with the millennium
"time-bomb" risk going out of business, the Confederation of
British Industry (CBI) warned today.
</P>
<P>
Adair Turner, CBI's director-general, said awareness of the
date change problem had increased dramatically, but warned there
was a "dangerous reluctance" among firms to convert that concern
into action to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
"While there are 732 days still to go to the millennium, the
final year must be used for preparation and testing. Firms need to
use next year to ensure they are compliant," he said.
</P>
<P>
The end of the century could create an international computer
meltdown. At midnight on the last day of 1999, when the year rolls
over to 2000, any computerized system which processes year dates
with only two digits will interpret the year 2000 as 1900.
</P>
<P>
The "millennium time-bomb" could affect almost every aspect of
daily life, including using credit cards, the payment of wages and
salaries and the provision of health services in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said many companies are reluctant to take action
despite the growing realization that the date change will affect
every company in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is simple and so is the solution. Failure to
implement it will cause major problems for British business," said
Turner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
