<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Elections Prolonged for at Least Another </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's general elections
dued to end today are to be prolonged for at least another day
following a general delay in the opening of the polling stations
across the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Commission has decided to extend polling in the affected
areas to 6:00 p.m. on 30th, December, 1997," said a statement
signed by Electoral Commission (EC) Chairman Samuel Kivuitu.
</P>
<P>
The statement said freak weather conditions in many parts of
the country and lateness in opening stations due to logistic
problems are key reasons behind the decision.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile there will be no counting of votes anywhere in the
country" until all the voting ends Tuesday, according to the
statement, which urges the police to continue "to keep maximum
security" during the polling period.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, EC Public Relations Officer Mahamed Koor told Xinhua
that the delay is common in the country mainly because of the
preparation of ballot papers and transport of 27,000 monitors to
a total of 12,754 polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 10 million registered Kenyan voters today queued up
orderly and peacefully to cast their ballots in Kenya's second
multi-party elections to choose the fittest person who will lead
this eastern African country into the next century.
</P>
<P>
All polling stations in the country were due to open at 6:00
a.m. for 12 hours. However, a lot of people complained about the
delay caused by the late-opening.
</P>
<P>
The polling station located in Highridge Primary School,
Westlands in Nairobi, saw the first vote cast there at 10:45 a.m.
although many voters arrived there four or five hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
Charity Ngilu, presidential hopeful for Social Democratic
Party, who cast her ballot in Kitui, Eastern Province, around
8:00 o'clock after waiting for over 90 minutes, also complained
about the postponement, said a report from the Kenya Television
Network (KTN).
</P>
<P>
"The Electoral Commission is ill-prepared," she said. Ngilu
who was listed the third in most opinion polls before the
elections, is one of the first two women in Kenya to vie for the
top seat.
</P>
<P>
Three flood-hit constituencies in Garissa, North-Eastern
Province, missed today's elections due to lack of transport for
officers and ballot papers, according to a latest report from the
KTN.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9,031,141 registered voters are expected to cast
their ballots to elect one president, 210 parliamentary members
and 2,955 local councillors.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's law, the winning presidential candidate must
garner the highest total and collect at least 25 percent of the
votes in at least five of the country's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls before today's elections show that President
Daniel arap Moi, 73 and in power for 19 years, would head the
poll with votes ranging from 40.2 percent to 49.2 percent, almost
doubling his closest challenger Mwai Kibaki, chairman of the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
But most people interviewed with Xinhua here today, which
include dozens of rich people of Asian origin, said they want a
change in the leadership, citing corruption, economic slump, poor
infrastructure, administration of low efficiency as key reasons.
</P>
<P>
Presidential candidate Setphen Omondi Oludhe, leader of the
tiny Economic Independence Party, announced his withdrawal Sunday
at the last minute, saying that he will support Moi, thus putting
the runners for the country's most crowded presidential race at
14.
</P>
<P>
A total of 883 candidates from 23 parties are running for
parliamentary seats while 8,446 vying for civic elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
