<HEADLINE> Iraq to Send More Pilgrims to Perform Hajj </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Iraq decided today to triple
the number of its pilgrims to Mecca, Saudi Arabia for the next
season, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3,000 Iraqis will be allowed to perform hajj as of
March next year, compared to 1,000 this year. The decision was
made at the 43rd session of Iraqi cabinet chaired by President
Saddam Hussein, INA said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting also sanctioned contacts with certain Arab
countries intended to recover their overdue debts to Iraq, in
order to meet the expenses needed for the upcoming pilgrimage,
INA said. It did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting also ordered the go-ahead of a motion with
the United Nations demanding that allocations be set aside for the
hajj from Iraqi oil proceeds under the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The deal between Iraq and the U.N. permits Baghdad to export 2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to buy food,
medicine and other humanitarian goods. 
</P>
