<HEADLINE> Britain Regrets Suspension of Contacts by Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Britain today expressed regret
over Turkish Cypriots' decision to suspend contacts with the
government of Cyprus controlled by Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
"we regret the decision to suspend bicommunal activity but we
very much hope that it will resume," a spokesman of the British
High Commission said here today.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the British High Commissioner to Cyprus David
Madden has to cancel a dinner party scheduled for Tuesday for 60
businessmen of the two sides, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He added that Madden is due to meet Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash later this week, during which he will raise the issue of
bicommunal contacts.
</P>
<P>
He said that Britain views such activity as positive and
constructive because it helps the two communities to understand
each other.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots controlling the northern third of Cyprus
Saturday decided to suspend most bicommunal activities, bilateral
peace talks and activities sponsored by foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The move is in response to the decision of this month by the
European Union to start accession talks with Cyprus next March,
but exclude Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Both the Turkish Cypriots and Turkey, which insist that Cyprus
can not join the EU until a solution is formulated to the Cyprus
problem, are opposed to EU's decision.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the mediterranean
island after a failed pro-Athens coup by the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and a number of countries have been making
efforts to help reunify the island in a bizonal, bicommunal
federation. But so far little tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
