<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Continue to Wreck Havoc in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The floods that devastated
southern Somalia are now playing havoc with the air traffic too.
</P>
<P>
The only tarmac road linking the capital Mogadishu with the
main airport of Ballidogle has been cut off by floods from the
Shabelle river, forcing a large number of local airlines to
suspend their routine operations.
</P>
<P>
The tarmac road is currently cut off near the district of
Wanlewein, 90 km southwest of Mogadishu, where a large bus TATA
was submerged in the middle of a large hole created by the strong
waters that gathered after the Shabelle river burst its banks in
the central part of the river and Hiran regions.
</P>
<P>
The companies who used the large planes are now hiring small
Cesna planes to land either at Km-50 or Issaley airstrips in an
effort to continue with some of their businesses. Other planes
changed their route to Nairobi where passengers can hire other
planes which can land at the gravel airstrips, north or south of
the capital.
</P>
<P>
All buses, lorries, trailers and the four-wheel-drive battle
wagons leaving for the southwestern regions stopped at the end of
the road where it is cut. Then a small home-made boat and porters
moved the people aboard the boat along with their goods across
the water.
</P>
<P>
This new business has been introduced after everything came to
a standstill for about 24 hours and now the people and their
goods are charged with a sum varying from less than one U.S.
Dollar to three Dollars to cross the water which stretches more
than 100 meters wide.
</P>
<P>
The floods have damaged villages and farms in Lower Shabelle
region. However, according to travellers, some of the displaced
people are now relieved a bit by feeding on fish and they were
seen fishing in the waters and catching many fish easily without
hooks or strings.
</P>
<P>
Some are using sharpened sticks and their clothes to catch
fish. Although the religion permits Somalis to eat fish, not many
of them go for fishing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the only bridge of Jalalaqsi district, 150 km north
of the capital, went down last night. Ibrahim Abdi Amey, deputy
district commissioner, said the bridge suddenly broke down after
two tractors passed it a little after midnight.
</P>
<P>
Amey told Xinhua through the VHF radio in Jalalaqsi town that
people in the town had to walk around for more than 20 km to
reach the other side of the same town. He noted that the town is
suffering from a new kind of disease which has claimed nine lives
in the past three days.
</P>
<P>
"A patient would complain about headache, then catches very
high fever, then blood comes out of the nostrils followed by
vomit and he or she passes away in less than 24 hours," Amey
said, adding, "The last one who died of the disease was an old
man who was buried this morning."
</P>
<P>
This mysterious disease has also been reported in the village
of Torotorow, 115 km southwest of Mogadishu, where more than 42
people have died.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the International Committee of Red Cross,
Somali Red Crescent Society and the World Health Organization who
visited the area, took samples from the sick and sent them to
Nairobi for identification.
</P>
<P>
Unlike in northeastern Kenya, no animals are reportedly dying
of the disease in any of these two places where the disease broke
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
