<HEADLINE> Trial of Coup Plotters Adjourned in Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The trial of seven Qataris
charged with involvement in a 1996 coup attempt has been adjourned
to January 4, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
A panel of three judges has made the decision after receiving
official documents from the state prosecutor general, which list
the charges, and the testimony of witnesses, the Gulf News quoted
a court official as saying.
</P>
<P>
No reason was given to the postponement.
</P>
<P>
The defendants, four military officers and three civilians,
have been accused of forming a clandestine group with the
intention of toppling Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa
al-Thani in February 1996, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
They have also been charged with contacting with foreigners
hostile to Qatar and revealing state secrets for money.
</P>
<P>
Two witnesses have alleged that the accused have been in
regular contacts with foreigners, supplying them with military
secrets of Qatar for money, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"The military officers were paid monthly according to their
ranks in the army and the others in lump sums," it quoted the head
of Qatar's criminal investigation department as saying.
</P>
<P>
"One of them traveled frequently to the United Arab Emirates
and stayed in room No. 605 at the Intercontinental Hotel in Abu
Dhabi and held meetings and dinners with members of a group
hostile to Qatar," the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
