<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The British government pledged
today to tighten security on Northern Ireland's Maze prison after
a loyalist guerrilla leader was gunned down by Republican inmates
in the jail.
</P>
<P>
Pro-British Protestant gunman Billy Wright was killed last
Saturday while serving imprisonment, which was followed by the
revenge killing of a former Irish Republican Army guerrilla
outside a hotel.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland prisons minister Adam Ingram said random
weekly searches would be introduced at the Maze and an inquiry
would held into the shooting of Wright and how guns were smuggled
into the jail.
</P>
<P>
"We are instituting a program of searches," he said at a news
conference held at the Maze prison near Belfast after holding an
emergency talk with Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam earlier
in the day..
</P>
<P>
Mowlam pledged that the "vicious, senseless murders" of Wright,
leader of the Loyalist Volunteer force, by members of the Irish
National Liberation Army and the revenge killing of a former IRA
gunman would not deflect the search for peace.
</P>
<P>
Three men charged with Wright's murder appeared in court at
Lisburn near Belfast today under tight security. 
</P>
