<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebel Stronghold Opened to Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A Sierra Leone state
television film crew and three international news agency
reporters including Xinhua were airlifted today aboard a military
helicopter here to visit a rebel stronghold in the east of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Kailahun, a place over 230 miles east of Sierra Leone, is
their destination where some 100 Kamajors militiamen were
captured Saturday by rebel combatants.
</P>
<P>
Rufus Ibrahim, commandant of the Revolutionary United Front
(RUF), said "the men surrendered after they were encircled at
Buedu."
</P>
<P>
"We also captured a lot of arms and ammunition including G3
weapons widely used only by the Nigerian contingent in ECOMOG,"
he claimed.
</P>
<P>
One of the surrendered Kamajors told Xinhua, "We were given
the impression that our mission will overrun Buedu but it was a
shock to see so many combatants guarding the town."
</P>
<P>
The team moved on to Kangama where the journalists met a
number of detained RUF dissidents including former top leaders
Fayia Musa, Philip Palmer and Ibrahim Deen-Jalloh.
</P>
<P>
They were involved in a leadership struggle to unseat rebel
leader Foday Sankoh in 1996 and were tried for treason by the
rebel organization and sentenced to death. Previous reports said
they had been executed.
</P>
<P>
Musa, a onetime spokesman for the RUF, looked frail and grey
haired. "We are Okay. We regretted to have plotted against the
organization which we set up to regain the freedom of all Sierra
Leoneans," he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Philip Palmer, another former member of the RUF, who was
tipped to replace Sankoh if the coup had succeeded, accused
deposed President Tejan Kabbah of "landing them in trouble."
</P>
<P>
He played a double role by promising us political and
financial support if we are to overthrow Sankoh and sign an
agreement of cooperation with his administration, Palmer added.
</P>
<P>
According to RUF commander Ibrahim, the lives of the
dissidents were saved as a result of the coup in May and the
unity between the rebels and the (military) government.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in seven years that the three towns
regarded as a major stronghold of the rebels have been opened to
"outsiders" including journalists.
</P>
<P>
The towns are perched on the fringes of the Liberian border
and heavily fortified by bazooka-carrying youngsters and bobby
traps with AA guns mounted on high ground. Women with babies
strapped to their backs till the rice farms with the assistance
of oxen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
