<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills Five in Mozambique in Three Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Five people have died of
cholera in the last three days in Mozambique, a senior health
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Avertino Barreto, deputy director of the National Health
Bureau, said here that the five deaths had been recorded since
last Saturday. Among them, three were reported in Xai-Xai,
capital of Gaza province, and two were from places outside the
capital Maputo.
</P>
<P>
A total of 267 new cholera patients were reported in the past
two days, putting the accelerated number in the country at 8,680.
</P>
<P>
However, Jose Chivale, head of the epidemic vigilance system
under the country's health ministry, said last Friday at a press
conference that the damage brought by cholera has been reduced
remarkably in the four southern provinces of Maputo, Gaza, Manica
and Inhambane, owing to the efforts made in improving the
environment and personal hygiene.
</P>
<P>
So far, 256 people have died of the epidemic since its
outbreak on August 13. However, the disease is only confined to
the four southern provinces. 
</P>
