<HEADLINE> No Technical Problem for Plane Crash in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The investigation team on
the December 15 Tajik aircraft crash in the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) today ruled out "technical failures," which have been widely
believed to be the reason of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
An initial analysis on the plane's digital flight data
recorder, commonly known as the black box, showed there is no
"technical failures in any part of the aircraft," UAE's Wam News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The analysis was from the UAE-CIS (Commonwealth of Independent
States) joint investigation team.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion is different from a senior UAE aviation
official's suggestion on December 16 that the accident was caused
by "engine problems."
</P>
<P>
Some other UAE officials who did not want to be named said the
plane might explode in mid-air, however, there was no official
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
Wam also said that medical analysis on the crew members of the
Tajik Tu-154 showed there was no narcotics in their blood.
</P>
<P>
There were nine crew members aboard when the plan crashed in
the UAE deserts. Eighty-five people were killed and Roberto
Serje, the co-pilot, was the only survivor. He is now in a
hospital in the UAE receiving treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Tu-154 Tajik aircraft crash was the second recorded air
disaster in the UAE. On September 23, 1983, an Abu Dhabi-bound
Gulf Air Boeing 737 coming from Karachi crashed in the UAE's
deserts, killing 112 people aboard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
