<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Turkmenistan Launche Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami stated here today that Iran and Turkmenistan have launched
a gas pipeline, a joint project aiming to send natural gas to
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Khatami made the remarks on his return from a two-day official
visit to Ashkhabad, saying that he and Turkmenian President
Saparmurat Niyazov Monday traveled to the eastern desert of
Turkmenistan and formally inaugurated the economically important
project.
</P>
<P>
Khatami arrived in Ashkhabad Sunday on his first foreign visit
since he was elected President in May.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline of 200 kilometers was built from Turkmenistan to
northern Iran at a cost of 195 million dollars, 80 percent of
which has been paid by Iran. It will deliver about 4 billion cubic
meters of natural gas a year to Iran and will be connected to
another pipeline to reach Europe via Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan, a former Soviet central Asian republic, is
desperately seeking a outlet for is huge natural gas reserves to
the rest of the world. Until now, it has only one export pipeline
through Russia which is competing with Turkmenistan in the world
gas market.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the presidents of Turkmenistan and Iran also
jointly inaugurated a project of fiber optics.
</P>
<P>
The fiber optics project, which was implemented by Iran's
telecommunications company in Turkmenistan, is a part of the
Asia-Europe fiber optics project from Shanghai, China and through
Iran to Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that the two countries would also build an oil
pipeline through Iran to the Persian Gulf to export Turkmenian crude
oil, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the two countries have discussed the issue of
building new oil pipeline during his visit, he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that the opening of the two projects would
promote the cooperation between Iran and Turkmenistan and would
also pave the way for Iran to speed up Iran's exports of
technology and manpower to the Central Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Officials from Iran and Turkmenistan also discussed the issue
of legal regime of the Caspian sea, Khatami said, voicing
Tehran's stand that all of the Caspian Sea littoral countries
should limit their exploration operations within the legal regime.
</P>
<P>
Iran repeatedly stated that the legal regime governing the
Caspian Sea has been provided for in the 1921 Iran-Russian
Treaty of Amity and the 1940 Commerce and Navigation Agreement
between Iran and former Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0030 </DOCNO>
