<HEADLINE> Kenyan Elections Extended to Tuesday Due to Bad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Bad weather conditions in
various parts of Kenya have forced the Electoral Commission to
make a decision to extend today's general elections for one more
day.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made this afternoon following a general delay
in the opening of the polling stations in this east African
country due to bad weather and poor transport.
</P>
<P>
In Mwingi District, a vehicle with ballot materials and
election officials was swept away this morning by the flooded
Enziu River near Nguni town.
</P>
<P>
All the six ballot boxes were however salvaged intact but two
pressure lamps were washed away along with the vehicle, the Kenya
News Agency (KNA) report today.
</P>
<P>
Francis Katua, District Election Co-ordinator, was quoted as
saying that heavy rains dumped in the area last night had
impaired the polling exercise in the district.
</P>
<P>
A total of six polling stations were kept waiting for six
hours as the vehicles carrying balloting materials got stuck at
Thokoa area, he added.
</P>
<P>
Peter Obilo, returning officer for Turkana South constituency,
today called for an arrangement to fly the ballot boxes to
polling stations in his constituency this morning when the ballot
boxes and papers have not arrived due to impassable roads.
</P>
<P>
In Tana River District, a helicopter is urgently needed to
airlift election officials and ballot boxes to flooded areas
within Galole constituency, the KNA reported.
</P>
<P>
About 200 officials including presiding officers and security
personnel deployed to the polling stations in the constituency
have been stranded at Hola Social Hall since Sunday waiting for
an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Three flooded constituencies in Garissa District, Northeastern
Province, missed today's elections due to lack of transport for
officers and ballot papers, according to a Kenya Television
Network report tonight.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Electoral Commission has decided to extend polling in
the affected areas to 6:00 p.m. Tuesday or on December 30.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the commission tonight said, "meanwhile
there will be no counting of votes anywhere in the country until
further notice from the commission." 
</P>
</TEXT>
