<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Oslo Peace Process in Dire Straits (By Zhi Linfei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Despite the short-lived
optimism created by January's signing of the Hebron redeployment
accord, the year 1997 witnessed the longest deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian Oslo peace process since it began four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Following Israel's start of building the controversial Har
Homa settlement in the hotly disputed East Jerusalem in March, the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process plunged into a seven-month-long
deadlock marked by sporadic violence and terrorist bombings.
</P>
<P>
The Har Homa project was part of the new Israeli government's
attempt to replace the land-for-peace principle, the corner-stone
of Oslo process, with the security-for-peace formula.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) halted
security cooperation and peace talks with Israel to register its
anger and protest. But this played into the hands of Israeli
government, which was in fact trying to derail the Oslo process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's expansion of existing settlements in the
Palestinian territories was also in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Israel's another major action to erode the Oslo process was
the deliberate delays in redeploying troops from the West
Bank. In early March, Israel unilaterally approved the scope of
the first stage of a three-phased troop redeployment at 9 percent,
which fell far short of the 30 percent as expected by the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The PNA rejected the unilaterally-set pullback only to provide
Israel a good excuse to delay also the second pullback, which
should have been completed by early September under the Hebron
accord.
</P>
<P>
The terrorism issue has become the most commonly used excuse
for Israel to delay the implementing of the signed agreements.
Following the July 30 and September 4 suicide bombing attacks in
two Jerusalem markets launched by Hamas, in which 25 people were
killed and hundreds of others wounded, Israel reacted quickly by
freezing transfer of land to pressure the PNA to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Although the freeze in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks was
broken in early October as a result of the efforts by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who visited the region
for the first time in late September, no substantial progress has
been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Israel's intransigence on security arrangements blocked any
real progress in the negotiations on the interim issues, including
opening the Gaza airport, building a Gaza seaport, and creating a
safe passage between the Palestinian self-rule Gaza Strip and West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
In late November, Israeli Cabinet, under tremendous pressure
from Washington which grew increasingly impatient with the lack of
progress in the peace process, approved in principle to carry out
the second troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu proposed to blend all the three stages of
redeployments in one operation as a part of the final-status
talks. The PNA blasted it as a ploy to avoid implementing the
signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Israel's deliberate derailment of the Oslo process
was apparently aimed at forcing the PNA to agree to enter
permanent talks when Israel is still at a dominant position
by holding up the further redeployments as crucial bargaining
chips.
</P>
<P>
It has become clear that Israel's bottom line is that it will
only hand over about 40-50 percent of West Bank to the PNA in the
final settlement, far short of the over 80 percent that the PNA is
dreaming of.
</P>
<P>
Being aware of the danger of accepting Israel's proposal for
bypassing the interim stage of the Oslo Process, PNA President
Yasser Arafat has been sticking to his demand for strict and
accurate implementation of the signed accords. In view of the huge
gap between the two sides, few can expect progress in near future.
</P>
<P>
In the coming year, the countdown to the Oslo process,
that is due to end in May 1999, will begin. In a warning
issued in November, Arafat declared that he would declare
Palestinian independence regardless of the Israeli opposition upon
the end of the Oslo process, but Netanyahu counter-threatened
that he would annex large parts of the West Bank if Arafat
does so.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent the collapse of Oslo process and push
forward the deeply-troubled Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, the
U.S. government and international community are expected to
increase pressure on both Israel and the PNA to narrow their
gap.
</P>
<P>
There are good reasons to fear for an escalated
Israeli-Palestinian tension if Israel continues refusing to return
to the course of Oslo process before it is too late. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
