<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urge for Changes Dominates Kenya's General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Although Kenyans varied much
over who they were voting for on the election day today, their
demands for social changes seemed to be dominating clearly on the
back of their minds.
</P>
<P>
"I want change," were the words of almost all voters who were
interviewed by Xinhua today. According to them, improvement in
state administrations is a key priority.
</P>
<P>
"Everything should get changes, especially the leadership,"
said a fashionable girl, who blamed the current government for
low efficiency, bad road transport, economic slow-down and
rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
The girl had been waiting for more than four hours outside the
polling station at the Highridge Primary School, Westlands, which
is one of the largest constituencies in the country. The station
was due to open at 6:00 a.m. but only saw the first vote cast
there at 10:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
"Even if (incumbent President Daniel arap) Moi retains his
power, changes must be made, otherwise the country will continue
to get worse," said a white middle-aged Kenyan who predicted that
the 73-year-old Moi, who was in power since 1978, would get
through as expected by many people.
</P>
<P>
Moi, when seeking his final five-year term, faces powerful
challengers including Mwai Kibaki of the Democratic Party,
Charity Ngilu of the Social Democratic Party, Raila Odinga of the
National Development Party and Kijana Wamalwa of FORD-Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Promises for change keynoted the three-week election campaigns
by the above so-called "Big Five" who all pledged to jump-start
the economy, remove corruptions, improve infrastructure, conduct
educational reforms, promote privatization and etc.
</P>
<P>
Many people said although issues like corruption, unemployment
and poor infrastructure might lead Moi to a possible Waterloo, he
was in great advantages due to sharp divisions in the Opposition
and to his most diluted tribal color.
</P>
<P>
However, it seems that common Kenyans choose their leaders
with much divided reasons and many of them vote in accordance
with their tribal line.
</P>
<P>
"Moi is good, I support him because he helps me get a job," a
young man working with the Ministry of Education told Xinhua on
his way to the polling station.
</P>
<P>
"I choose Moi because he loves peace," said a nurse working
for a Chinese clinic in downtown Nairobi. Moi is recognized home
and abroad as a prominent and active peace-broker in east Africa
and the Horn of Africa region.
</P>
<P>
"Why we voted for Kibaki? Because he is an economist," said
an aged Asian-origin couple when leaving the polling station.
</P>
<P>
"I have voted for Kibaki because he has more experiences in
the management of political and economic affairs," said Gitonga
Njorogo, a 22-year-old student, after casting his ballot.
</P>
<P>
"I will vote for Odinga. He is from my tribe," said a security
personnel working for a foreign media institution. He is a Luo
from western Nyanza province.
</P>
<P>
"By the way, I'm not ready to vote for a woman (C. Ngilu)," he
added. Ngilu is one of the first two women ever to vie for the
top seat in Kenya. They have attracted many voters, especially
educated people in urban areas due to her strong calls for
changes and her fresh image untainted by scandals.
</P>
<P>
"Men have ruled the country for a long time. May women prove
they are better," said a Luo girl working for a non-governmental
organization here, who will cast her ballot in favor of Ngilu.
</P>
<P>
More than nine million registered voters today formed long
queues to elect one president, 210 parliamentary members and
2,955 local councillors across this east African country with a
population of some 28 million.
</P>
<P>
All polling stations in the country were scheduled to open at
6:00 a.m. for 12 hours but delay was common, which forced the
polling to be extended to Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's law, the winning presidential candidate must
garner the highest total and collect at least 25 percent of the
votes in at least five of Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
A total of 883 candidates from 23 parties are running for the
parliamentary seats while 8,446 vying for civic elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
