<HEADLINE> Zambian Siamese Twins to Be Separated in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- South African and
foreign neurosurgeons will work together Tuesday to try to
separate 11-month-old Siamese twins from Zambia, in an operation
expected to take at least 20 hours.
</P>
<P>
The team, which comprises neurosurgeons from South Africa, the
United States, Zambia and other countries, would perform the
operation at Garankuwa hospital in Pretoria, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The hospital's superintendent, Dr. Reg Broekmann, said today
that the boys, Luka and Joseph Banda, were joined at the top of
their heads and preliminary tests had indicated that they
probably had separate brains.
</P>
<P>
Broekmann said the operation was being done in South Africa at
the request of the Zambian government, since Zambia did not have
the necessary facilities.
</P>
<P>
If all goes well, the operation might be completed Tuesday, he
said. But it was also likely that the operation take two phases,
10 days within each other.
</P>
<P>
Should this be the case, the twins would have to rest for 10
days to allow new veins to develop before the second part of the
operation can proceed, Broekmann said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
