<HEADLINE> US Welcomes Norway's Role in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. said today that it
welcomes Norway's interest in reviving Middle East peace talks
despite unflattering remarks by Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut
Vollebaek about the U.S. role in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The Norwegians have long played an extremely helpful role in
the Middle East peace process, and so we would certainly welcome
their continued efforts," said State Department spokesman James
Foley.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian-sponsored secret talks led to a significant
breakthrough between Israel and the Palestinians in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Foley said he does not believe the Norwegian initiative will
disrupt the American effort.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek plans to travel to the Middle East next month for
talks with Israeli and Palestinian leaders. He said the talks the
two sides have had with Washington can be useful for a while "but
it's obvious that it's limited."
</P>
<P>
Foley rejected that characterization, pointing out that U.S.
diplomats helped restart the process after setbacks this past
summer brought on by terrorist bombings. 
