<HEADLINE> U.S. Discourages Lantos' Interest in Visiting Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S State Department on
Monday confirmed that Democratic Representative Tom Lantos had
expressed his interest in visiting Iran but was discouraged by the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
"He has expressed an interest in visiting Iran but let me
emphasize should he actually be traveling to Iran it would not
be at the request of the White House or the State Department,"
State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the White House denied a report from a Gulf
state's official news agency that Lantos had been sent by the
Clinton administration to Tehran in an effort to find any
evidence for the changes of Iranian foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
"We have no plans to send a special envoy to Tehran at all,"
White House spokesman Eric Rubin said. The reported visit was
"news to us," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Foley confirmed that, although the Clinton administration
had not sent Lantos to Tehran as a special envoy, Lantos himself
expressed his wishes to go there.
</P>
<P>
Foley, however, said it was something "that we would
discourage."
</P>
<P>
"It is not something that we encourage and again if he were to
travel he would not be traveling as special envoy or as a
representative of the United States government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Foley told reporters that Lantos, a California Democrat and a
senior member of the House of Representatives International
Relations Committee, had been in touch with both the State
Department and the White House to discuss a possible trip to
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Lantos's talks of traveling to Tehran came at a time when
both Iranian and U.S. leaders voiced conciliatory remarks over
the relations between the two countries, which severed their
diplomatic relations after 1979 Islamic revolution in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami, who won a presidential
election in May, expressed his hope to restore dialogue with the
United States at a news conference in Tehran on December 14 and
U.S. President Bill Clinton responded two day later with a
positive tone for that proposal.
</P>
<P>
"I think it was a tragic that the United States was
separated from the people of Iran," Clinton said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed the U.S. position for the possible dialogue,
saying three issues should be discussed before any dialogue
could be considered.
</P>
<P>
The three allegations include: Iran's support and funding for
terrorism, opposition to the U.S.-sponsored Middle East peace
process and its development of weapons of mass destruction, all
of which the Iranian government has flatly denied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
