<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Forced to Consider Withdrawing State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- After a major defeat in the
Knesset (parliament) today, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is now considering to withdraw the 1998 state budget
draft from Knesset (parliament), local radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Likud government suffered major
budget defeat in the Knesset this afternoon as it lost the
votes to the opposition on the budget arrangements bill by 7
ballots, 48 to 55.
</P>
<P>
In today's vote, the coalition ministers David Levy, Yehoshua
Matza, Natan Sharansky and Yuli Edelstein did not show up
for the vote.
</P>
<P>
All seven Yisrael Ba'aliya Knesset members were absent and
three Gesher Knesset members voted against the government.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 coalition Knesset members has declared recently that
they opposed all or part of the budget arrangements bill and
refused to vote for the new state budget, which include a 2.3
billion shekels (about 660 million U.S. dollars) cut.
</P>
<P>
Members of small parties in the coalition government have been
demanding more shares of the budget for their respective
ministries, refusing to accept the cuts.
</P>
<P>
Limor Livnat, minister from the leading Likud party in the
government, said today she believed that the best way for Netanyahu
is to withdraw the current budget and submitted another one before
March 31 following the government defeat today.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible according to the legislation, we can throw it
into the end of March. And I think this would be the best idea,
because if it can not be passed now, I do think we have to pay
more for other coalition parties."
</P>
<P>
By law, the state budget must be passed into law by midnight on
December 31, and the vote is automatically one of confidence in
the government. However, if the government fails it then has a
three-month probationary period to reverse the situation and get
the budget passed.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu denied Sunday night that he had been making great
concession to his coalition partners on the 1998 state budget in
an effort to gain their support for passing it by its December 31
deadline.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government had reduced the national deficit by
7 billion shekels (about 2 billion dollars) and this was a "major
achievement" though conceding that such cuts caused "suffering
and problems." 
</P>
</TEXT>
