<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Official Visits Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Commander-in-Chief of
U.S. Central Command Anthony Zinni paid a brief visit to Bahrain
today on bilateral military cooperation, the Bahraini news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Zinni held talks with Bahrain's Defense Minister Sheikh Khalifa
bin Ahmad al Khalifa on military cooperation between the two
countries and the latest developments in the Gulf region, the news
agency said, without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources in Bahrain said the U.S. general also inspected
U.S. air forces based in Bahrain's Sheikh Aesi air base during his
visit.
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 60 U.S. warplanes were deployed in the
Bahraini air base as part of U.S. military buildup over the Iraqi
weapons inspection standoff.
</P>
<P>
Washington began to beef up its military presence in the Gulf
region last month after Iraqi President Saddam Hussein ordered
the expulsion of American members of U.N. weapons inspection
team.
</P>
<P>
U.S. military officials said that the entire U.S. 347th Air
Expeditionary Wing, including about 1,000 ground support staff, is
in the Gulf region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
