<HEADLINE> Pak PM Vows to Remove Shortcomings from Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif on Tuesday vowed to remove contradictions and
shortcomings from the country's Constitution and bring it in line
with the interests of the nation.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when addressing the Parliamentary Party
meeting of the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (Nawaz) and its
allies at the PM Secretariat here.
</P>
<P>
"We will introduce a package of constitutional amendments to
restore the Constitution in its true spirit and bring it in line
with the interests of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that while achieving this objective, it is
imperative to remain above party interests.
</P>
<P>
He said, the clauses pertaining to Islamic injunctions in the
unanimously accepted 1973 Constitution will be retained as they
are extremely useful.
</P>
<P>
"By maintaining the political stability brought about by the
13th Amendment and by pursuing our healthy policies, we will be
able to steer the country to an economic turnaround within a
couple of years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Amendment, which was adopted by the parliament on
April 1, has abolished the presidential powers to dissolve an
elected government and dismiss the Prime Minister. 
