<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Recommends No Travel Restrictions amid Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) does not recommend travel restrictions despite an outbreak
of a disease of unknown origin in northeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
In a press release here on Monday, WHO emphasized that the
disease is not a threat to tourists in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Dr David Heymann, Director of WHO's Division of Emerging and
other Communicable Diseases, was quoted as saying that the disease
has occurred in a very remote rural area of northeastern Kenya,
near the border with Somalia, and the area is far away from the
tourist centers of Nairobi, Mombassa and the national parks.
</P>
<P>
WHO, together with Kenyan health officials and non-governmental
organizations, currently has teams investigating the outbreak in
Kenya and in Somalia south of Mogadishu, where a second localized
outbreak is suspected to have occurred.
</P>
<P>
Due to the difficulty of access to the region involved, the
full extent of the outbreak is not yet known but reports indicate
that up to 250 people may have died from the disease.
</P>
<P>
Similar disease and deaths in domestic animals, goats, sheep,
cattle and camels, have been reported in the same area, according
to WHO. Initial epidemiological data from Kenya do not support the
diagnosis of Ebola haemorrhagic fever as a cause of the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
WHO said that anthrax bacillus, and other infectious agents
such as yellow fever and Rift Valley fever, all of which are known
to be endemic in the region, are currently being considered as
possible causes of this outbreak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
