<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Banks React Over S.Korean Debt Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) - British banks are taking
reacting measures to the financial crisis in South Korea as part
of a global effort to launch a credit loans to the country.
</P>
<P>
HSBC Holdings, the world's largest commercial banking group,
said it was organizing a group of London banks to consider their
South Korean loans.
</P>
<P>
A HSBC official said last night: "We are the co-ordinating bank
for the London group and a meeting took place this morning. There
is a series of meetings planned."
</P>
<P>
Bank of England figures show that UK banks had loans
outstanding to South Korea of 3.5 billion pounds (6 billion US
dollars) at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, figures show that domestic machinery orders
fell 34.6 percent in the year to November, against a 29.8 percent
rise in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Domestic construction orders fell 23.3 percent in November,
compared with a 48.5 percent rise in November 1996, suggesting
that investment is being dramatically cut.
</P>
<P>
While banks around the world appeared ready to roll
over existing loans to Korean banks, they remained deeply
divided on whether to lend new money to the country.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England declined to comment on suggestions
that it had advised British banks to roll over loans to
South Korean companies that may come due in the next few
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
