<HEADLINE> 2 Million Ethiopians Face Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Over two million people
in Ethiopia's Amhara Region will face food shortage in the coming
1998, the Regional Disaster Prevention and Preparedness
Commission has announced in Bahirdar, capital city of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency said in a report today that the
number of people in need of relief food in 1998 will rise to over
two million from previous year's 1.44 million owing to delayed
and irregular seasonal rains in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The commission estimated that only 4.8 million tons of grain
will be harvested this year, which is 24 percent short of the
demands
</P>
<P>
It noted that 290,000 tons of relief food will be
required, adding that 80 percent of the needy will be favored
through food-for-work programs to prevent possible future
dependency. 
</P>
