<HEADLINE> Philippine government, Rebels Defer Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the secessionist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have finally
set their next meeting on February 2-3 in southern Mindanao, a
rebel leader said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military affairs, said
that chief government negotiator Orlando Soriano has recently
agreed to the request by the MILF to defer the date of the
scheduled meeting from January to February.
</P>
<P>
Murad said this will enable the MILF to religiously observe the
Holy Month of Ramadhan on January next year.
</P>
<P>
According to Murad, the talks was first scheduled on December
22-23 but was postponed on request by the government peace panel
whose members cited Christmas celebration as reason.
</P>
<P>
"In return," he said, "the government panel likewise granted
our request in order for us to be also with our love ones during
Ramadhan."
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be held in Marawi city, capital of Lanao del
Sur Province, will discuss the agenda for reaching a preliminary
peace agreement between the MILF and the government, Murad said.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF), is currently the largest Muslim rebel
group in the country, with an estimated membership of 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF signed a permanent peace agreement with the government
in September 1996, but the MILF refused to be included in the
agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
