<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State State Approves Building of China's Largest Sea Bridge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- State Council, China's highest
governing body, has approved an enormous project, the Lingdingyang
Bridge spanning the sea between Zhuhai and Hong Kong, according to
local government sources.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the six-lane bridge, which will be 27
kilometers long and 33 meters wide, will cost about 16.6 billion
yuan (two billion U.S. dollars) in dynamic investment and take six
years to complete, said Liang Guangda, secretary of Zhuhai city
committee of the Communist Party of China, at a news conference
here today.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five percent of registered construction capital will come
from the state and Guangdong provincial departments of
transportation and Zhuhai city, Liang said, and 45 percent from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
The Lingdingyang Bridge Project Company will be responsible for
raising extra funds and operating the whole project, the largest
sea bridge in China.
</P>
<P>
Zhuhai, one of five special economic zones in China, faces Hong
Kong across the Lingdingyang Sea.
</P>
<P>
As another passage linking Hong Kong and inland areas, the
bridge is expected to ease road traffic through Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of departments and research institutes have been
involved in feasibility studies of the project since 1992,
including studies of seismology, environmental protection,
geology, hydrology and ocean transportation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and British governments began discussing the
project in 1995. The results were approved by the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region after Hong Kong's return to China on
July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
