<HEADLINE> China Pledges Involvement in S. Africa's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said today that China is ready to
help South Africa in its reconstruction and national development.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate very much the program of reconstruction and
development that was formulated by the government of South
Africa," Qian told a news conference jointly held with South
African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo.
</P>
<P>
"China stands ready to be involved in the development in South
Africa, in particular, in the fields of rural housing, education,
power supply and communications."
</P>
<P>
Before the news conference, Qian and Nzo signed a joint
communique to establish diplomatic relations between the two
countries as from January 1, 1998, as well as five other
agreements, including a package of aid from China.
</P>
<P>
Qian said South Africa is a major country in Africa while
China is the biggest country in Asia. "The establishment of
friendly relations and cooperation between China and South
Africa, undoubtedly, is in the interests of our two peoples and
also in the interests of world peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian announced that China will set up consulate generals in
Johannesburg, Cape Town and Durban and that China has appointed
Wang Xuexian, Director of the Chinese Center for South African
Studies, as its first ambassador to South Africa. The appointment
has won consent from the South African side, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nzo told the press conference that South Africa will benefit
from the friendly relations with China, which has a vibrant
economy and is a permanent member of the United Nations Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
"Now South Africa has added one more ally to that important
organ of international community (the UN), which should make it
easier for us to play our part and role in international politics
in the interests of the defense of peace and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa's relationship with China was
long-standing, and the establishment of diplomatic relations with
it represents a continuation of friendship between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Referring to South Africa's severance of ties with Taiwan, Nzo
said: "It was inevitable that South Africa would come to a
position of recognizing international practice."
</P>
<P>
"The government of the Republic of South Africa recognizes
that there is but one China in the world, the government of the
People's Republic of China is the sole legal government
representing the whole of china and recognizes China's position
that Taiwan is an inalienable part of China," the joint
communique says.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela declared in November
1996 that South Africa would sever ties with Taiwan and recognize
the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who is in South Africa for a five-day visit, has met
Mandela and some other South African leaders. He is expected to
open the Chinese Embassy in Pretoria on Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
