<HEADLINE> Cultural Exchanges Increase Between China's inland and Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Cultural exchanges between
China's inland areas and the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) hit a new record in 1997 in terms of the number of
exchange programs and people involved.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, the number of such activities arranged
by the Chinese Ministry of Culture had reached 520, involving
6,571 people.
</P>
<P>
Most of the exchanges embody the theme marking the return of
Hong Kong, such as a photo exhibition on Hong Kong's history and
development, a collection of musical works on Hong Kong's return
and an exhibition of Chinese arts.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between mainland and Hong Kong artists, traditional
Chinese arts and artistic academic exchanges constitute the major
characteristics of cultural exchanges between the two in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Cultural exchanges between China's inland areas and Macao also
increased rapidly during 1997, with the total reaching 79 and
involving 1,149 people.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Culture said that increasing
cultural exchanges between China's inland areas and Hong Kong, and
with Macao, are helpful in promoting further understanding and
development between the two sides, and are helpful for cultural
prosperity and development of the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
