<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Graduates Favor Jobs With Big Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Most Macao graduates have
dropped their idea of becoming a government employee for the first
time, and chosen to be employed by big companies instead, a sample
survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Co-conducted in September and October among 150 young graduates
by the Macao Foundation and the Education and Youth Department of
Macao, the survey shows that most graduates have shifted their
idea of becoming a government employee to being one of a brand
name company.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, graduated students of middle
schools and colleges dreamed to be a civil servant as the salary
of government employee is usually five to six times those with
ordinary companies.
</P>
<P>
As a result, competitions became increasingly fiercer. There
were usually several hundred people trying to seek one post with
the government offices.
</P>
<P>
According to results of the survey which was made public this
month, it usually took a graduate one and half months to get a
job. Most of the respondents are now working as clerks and
teachers, with none as vendors, farmers or fishermen.
</P>
<P>
The survey also finds that their average monthly salary reached
between 5,000 and 6,000 patacas (625 U.S. dollars to 700 U.S.
dollars), and they usually worked between eight to nine hours a
day.
</P>
<P>
About 46 percent of the respondents were women. A total of 130
out of the 150 surveyed were graduates of colleges in Macao and
China's inland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
