<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy to Maintain Steady Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of a "soft
landing" and significant improvement in macro-economic conditions,
China's economy will continue its momentum of fast development and
low inflation in 1998, said Ye Zheng, a spokesman with the State
Statistical Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
Ye said today that China has an ample stock of commodities,
with a lot of bottlenecks in infrastructure largely eased and
investment conditions upgraded. In addition, the new policies made
by the 15th national congress of the Communist Party of China has
triggered a stronger reform wave to streamline the country's
economic system.
</P>
<P>
All these positive factors will play a bigger role next year,
and guarantee a robust growth in investment and consumption as
well as a fairly stable import volume, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a strong demand for investment is expected to
emerge in agriculture, infrastructure facilities and
high-technology sectors in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the per capita income of people in both urban and
rural areas this year went up by 2.9 percent and 4 percent,
respectively, providing a sound basis for further increases in
domestic consumption next year.
</P>
<P>
The central government reduced interest rates twice this year,
and thus enhance the potential for both investment and
consumption. Such positive effects caused by the last interest
rate cut will surface early next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ye acknowledged that the country could slow its pace in
attracting foreign investment because of the ongoing financial
crisis in Southeast Asia and the widespread wait-and-see attitude
of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the huge market potential, in addition to the
improved investment conditions and government's preferential
policies here, should keep China favorable for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Ye said the currency depreciation in Southeast Asian nations
will not cause serious impacts on China's imports next year,
because China now has a more comprehensive import mix and cheaper
labor than its rivals in Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Extremists Demonstrate in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of members of the
Jewish extremist group, the Temple Mount Faithfuls, held a
protest march today in East Jerusalem as the Muslim holy month
Ramadan started.
</P>
<P>
Escorted by armed police, the protesters marched from the
Damascus Gate of the Old City to the outside of the Temple
Mount, where the third holiest Muslim shrine the Aksa mosque
stands.
</P>
<P>
They later marched on to the Orient House, the de facto
office of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) in East
Jerusalem. To avoid possible disturbances, police prevented the
group from burning the PNA flags before the building.
</P>
<P>
The Temple Mount Faithfuls advocates rebuilding the destroyed
holy Jewish temple on the Temple Mount. Every year, the group
has been trying to march into the Temple Mount compound to
assert Israeli claim over the holy place, but they were denied
entry by police for fear of sparking widespread violence between
Jews and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Gershon Salomon, leader of the Temple Mount Faithfuls,
charged today the secret agency General Security Service (GSS)
for provoking his group and other Jewish rightist groups in
order to prosecute them.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that two Jewish extremists Avigdor Eskin and
Haim Pakovitch, who were arrested recently for trying to throw
pig heads into the Temple Mount during Ramadan, are in fact
GSS provocateurs. The two were brought on trial Sunday in Tel
Aviv on charges of provoking violence.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing police Inspector General, Assaf Hefetz, warned
earlier this week that Jewish extremists are planning to damage
the Muslim holy shrines in East Jerusalem and destroy the
peace process. He called on Israeli religious leaders and
rightwing politicians to strain the extremists and condemn their
provoking actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
