<HEADLINE> Tibet Digging Out from Heavy Snowfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Governments at all levels in
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region are battling the effects
of snowstorms which have caused serious problems in the region, an
official from the regional government said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ciren Sanzhu, vice-chairman of the regional government, said in
an interview with Xinhua that the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State Council have
expressed deep concerns about the disaster in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to Ciren, snowstorms started in September and
expanded to six prefectures and cities in the region in December.
</P>
<P>
Nagqu Prefecture reported snowfall 40 times since September,
including five heavy storms in 11 counties.
</P>
<P>
Starting on Dec. 9, heavy snowfall expanded to 40 counties in
six prefectures and cities in the region, with the snowfall in
some places reaching 95 mm within 24 hours, he added.
</P>
<P>
The snow reportedly is the heaviest since Tibet began keeping
meterological records, and the minimum temperature in some
locations is 34 degrees Celsius below zero, the vice-chairman said.
</P>
<P>
A group of townships and villages suffered blackouts because of
the snow, Ciren said.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the central government, the regional
government has allocated 27.25 million yuan in relief funds for
disaster relief along with large quantities of grain, foods, fuel,
clothes, and instruments.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice-chairman, the regional government has
decided to grant 4.9 million yuan more in relief funds for 50,000
snowstorm victims, along with 400,000 liters of fuel.
</P>
<P>
He said that governments at all levels, the masses of people,
cardres and workers from local government agencies and armed
forces in the region all have joined the efforts to fight against
snowstorm-related damage. No deaths have been reported, however.
</P>
<P>
Ciren said he is convinced that the region will win the fight
with the help of the central government and people from across the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
