<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Tourist Market to Soften in 1998: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The rapidly growing
Australian tourist industry was predicted to be softening next
year in the wake of the Asian currency crisis, a spokesman from
the Tourism Ministry said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said the general view was the Asian fallout would
probably kick in mid-way through next year, or even a little
earlier.
</P>
<P>
"We will see some deceleration of growth but we don't expect to
go into negative growth," the spokesman was quoted by the
Australian Associated Press (AAP) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Australian Tourist Commission Chief John Morse predicted 1998
would not be an easy year for the tourist industry and would be
particularly tough for the airlines.
</P>
<P>
"It could be one of the toughest years on record for the
airline industry in respect of competition and airfares with a lot
more code sharing of routes," Morse said.
</P>
<P>
"But I'm still quite confident about Asia in the mid to
long-term and those economies are going to come back around the
turn of the century."
</P>
<P>
He said, meanwhile, the tourist industry would look more to the
U.S. and European markets which had experienced growth due to the
devaluation of the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Training Australia Chief Executive Bill Galvin conceded
1998 would be challenging. He said tourism was still a major
growth industry with 55,000 new jobs, or six percent jobs growth,
to be created.
</P>
<P>
However, Australian Tourist Commission Managing Director Bruce
Baird said he did not believe the industry would reach a projected
jobs growth of six percent next year, saying that it was more
likely to be closer to three percent.
</P>
<P>
"The fact is the tourism has been hit by the South-East Asian
currency problems and so that the number of people coming from
Asia, which is a major source for us, has been slowing," Baird
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
