<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The first election-related
violence took place in Jaffna in Northern Sri Lanka Monday as a
candidate of the Eelam People's Democratic Party (EPDP) was
stabbed by members of another political party, reports reaching
here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
EPDP candidate Kandiah Paramalingam, 40, was beaten by members
of the People's Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam (PLOTE) and
stabbed by a broken bottle in Velanai, Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The candidate who is contesting for a village council post
sustained serious injury and was admitted to the Jaffna General
Hospital. It's reported that he is still in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the incident, an argument took place between the PLOTE
members, who went to the town to open a party office and launch
their election campaign, and local residents who staged a protest
against their presence, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
EPDP leader Douglas Devananda has brought the incident to the
notice of PLOTE leader D. Sitharthan.
</P>
<P>
The first local government elections in ten years in the Jaffna
region will be held on January 29, 1998. A total of 571,484 voters
are to cast their ballots at 422 polling stations to elect 234
representatives for municipal, urban and village councils in
Jaffna and Kilinochchi districts in the north.
</P>
<P>
About 1171 candidates are to run the elections.  
</P>
