<HEADLINE> Prison-Based Industries to Be Upgraded in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's new Prisons
Director-General Omar Mohamed Dan Tuesday pledged to upgrade
prison-based industries to help jails be self-financing and less
dependent on government funds.
</P>
<P>
Omar formally took over the post Tuesday from out-going
director-general Zaman Khan who retires tomorrow, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The new prisons chief, who was promoted from the post of the
deputy director-general, said that he was preparing a proposal
paper on the above issue, which would include, among other things,
a proposal for the appointment of marketing officers from among
prison staff to promote products made by inmates nation-wide to
the public, Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper would also spell out the Prisons Department's further
cost-cutting measures, Omar told reporters Tuesday in Kajang, some
20 kilometers south from here, after taking over the post.
</P>
<P>
Omar said the department would foster closer rapport with the
private sector to modernize prison-based industries including
buying new machines and introducing the latest approach in skills
training.
</P>
<P>
Inmates in Malaysia have been churning out products such as
furniture, handicrafts, clothing and carpets for sale to the
public.
</P>
<P>
Omar was quoted as saying "Prison-based industries involving 35
jails nation-wide saw a turnover of 4.5 million ringgit (1.165
million U.S. dollars) in 1996 compared with only 3 million ringgit
(0.7 million U.S. dollars) in the previous year." 
</P>
