<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Readjusts Tax on Imported Equipment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to provide
more preferential terms for foreign and domestic companies,
including tax exemptions for imported equipment, as of January 1,
1998.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu Yi said
that related imported equipment will be used for projects
encouraged by the State.
</P>
<P>
The goal of tax readjustments, initiated by the State Council,
is to attract increasing foreign investment, encourage the import
of more advanced foreign technology and equipment, enhance the
adjustment of the industrial structure and technological
advancement, and maintain rapid, sound and sustainable national
economic development, according to Wu.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the preferential terms cover tax exemptions for
imported equipment for internal use by enterprises listed in the
directory for foreign-funded industries, and encourage foreign
companies to invest in high-tech industries, infrastructure and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Domestic projects, provided they are in industries which the
State has prioritized for development, will also receive tax
exemptions for imported equipment for self-use, said Wu.
</P>
<P>
Domestic projects funded with loans from international
financial institutions or with foreign government loans will
receive more extensive preferential terms than projects using
domestic funding, including the same terms foreign-funded projects
receive for imported equipment if they are located in central and
west China, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to support the processing trade, increase
employment and expand exports, imported equipment, with the
exception of items listed on the compulsory tax list, will be
exempt from taxes.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the Customs department will release two lists on
December 31, one for foreign firms and the other for domestic
firms. The lists will outline imported commodities subject to tax
levies.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the goal for levying taxes on some imported
commodities is to discourage the importation of low-technology
machinery and equipment which can be built in sufficient
amounts domestically, and to protect fledgling domestic
industries still under development.
</P>
<P>
The list for foreign-funded projects covers taxable items with
levies lower than projects using domestic investment, in order to
ensure that foreign investors have a greater leeway in purchasing
equipment. The goal is to attract more foreign investment and
promote national economic development, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
This is the common practice pursued by developing nations, said
Wu, adding that projects involving domestic investment should use
more domestically manufactured products with guaranteed supplies.
</P>
<P>
She cited the following areas in which foreign investment is
encouraged:
</P>
<P>
-- fields related to new agricultural technology, as well as
the comprehensive development of agriculture, energy, transport
and important raw materials:
</P>
<P>
-- advanced and high technology and new equipment and
materials, which can improve the functions of products, conserve
energy and raw materials, enhance the economic and technological
efficiency and economic returns of businesses, and which cater to
the needs of the market, especially items with an inadequate
production capacity in China;
</P>
<P>
-- sectors that meet the needs of the international market,
upgrade products, open up new markets and increase exports;
</P>
<P>
-- new technology and equipment for the comprehensive use of
resources and renewable resources, or for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
-- projects which can bring into full play the advantages of
central and west China in labor and resources, and which comply
with the state industrial policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Readjusts Tax on Imported Equipment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The minister also cited the following projects using domestic
investment which are encouraged by the state:
</P>
<P>
-- those which currently meet and will continue to meet market
needs for the foreseeable future, and those with bright
development prospects;
</P>
<P>
-- those which have a high technological content, help to renew
equipment and accelerate the technological upgrading of
traditional industries, optimize and upgrade China's industrial
structure, and improve the overall economic returns;
</P>
<P>
-- those which China has the technological potential to
develop and which will fill in the gap in industry and
technology, and which help create new economic growth areas;
</P>
<P>
-- those which comply with China's sustainable development
strategy, and which will help to conserve resources and raw materials,
and which are conducive to ecological and environmental
protection; and
</P>
<P>
-- those which will increase China's supply capacity.
</P>
<P>
Wu explained that the undertaker of a project involving
domestic investment should handle with a local custom office the
procedures for tax exemptions on imported equipment for self-use,
on the strength of a "confirmation certificate" issued by related
government departments which have approved his feasibility
study report.
</P>
<P>
With regard to foreign-funded projects, procedures for the
exemption of taxes on imported equipment should be handled with a
local customs office, on the strength of the "confirmation
certificate," a business license and documents that approve the
establishment of a foreign-funded enterprise.
</P>
<P>
A company undertaking processing trade that imports
non-evaluated equipment provided by an overseas company should
handle with a local customs office the procedures for import duty
exemptions, on the strength of an approved processing trade
contract.
</P>
<P>
The term "confirmation certificate" refers to documents that
require projects to conform to requirements on the two lists.
</P>
<P>
Wu said foreign-funded enterprises will enjoy preferential
treatment immediately after they complete importing equipment and
raw materials for self-use approved for exemptions from tariffs
and value-added taxes prior to March 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Equipment imported for technological upgrading projects
approved prior to March 31, 1996, will be exempted from taxation
starting from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Other projects, with the exception of those included on the
compulsory lists, will be exempted from taxation from January 1,
1998. These include foreign-funded projects and projects involving
domestic investment approved between April 1, 1996 and December
31, 1997, as well as those receiving approval to import equipment
with foreign government loans and loans from international
financial institutions between January 1, 1995 and December 31,
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
