<HEADLINE> S. Africa Vows to Expand Cooperation With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa hopes to expand
its cooperation with China, especially on international issues,
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed... that our cooperation in international
questions should be raised to higher levels," Nzo told a joint
press conference with Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen after the signing of a joint communique to establish
diplomatic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said: "South Africa and China are not only going to realize
a steady growth in our bilateral relations, but we shall endeavor
as two countries to contribute as much as possible in
international relations, in defense of humanity against possible
catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
Nzo said he held important discussions with Qian, which laid a
firm basis for further cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that South Africa's African National Congress had
close relationship with China and the Chinese Communist Party
even before South Africa's democratic transformation.
</P>
<P>
Nzo announced that South Africa has appointed Chris Dlamini as
its first ambassador to China. Dlamini is currently Chief of the
South African Center for Chinese Studies in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said he has accepted an invitation from Qian to visit China
and that he is looking forward for such a visit.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that Chinese President Jiang Zemin would be able to
visit South Africa "in a not too distant future."
</P>
<P>
He said bilateral trade had already been very active before
the establishment of diplomatic relations between China and South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries will reach 1.6 billion U.S.
Dollars by the end of the year, Nzo said, adding that it is a
very firm beginning, which gives hopes that trade relations will
be further developed to benefit the two peoples. 
</P>
