<HEADLINE> China Making Changes in Border Inspection Troop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The State Council has decided
to transform the system of military service among China's border
inspectors into a professional group on a trial basis in hopes of
increasing competence and stability.
</P>
<P>
Both the recently established border inspection general
stations in Beijing and Shenzhen and general stations which will
be set up in the cities of Tianjin, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Zhuhai,
Shantou, Xiamen and Haikou before June of 1998, are expected to be
placed under the control of the Ministry of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the ministry said the border inspection
troop inspects and supervises personnel and transportation coming
in and out of ports opened to foreigners, and they shoulder the
important mission of safeguarding state sovereignty and security.
</P>
<P>
The deepening of reforms, the rapid development of the national
economy, the increasing number of personnel and transportation
means coming in and out of ports opened to foreigners, together
with the rising number of illicit migration all combine to
emphasize the need for a highly competent professional troop.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that the establishment of a professional
troop would be conducive to carrying out the central government's
policies and orders and promoting exchanges between China and the
rest of the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
