<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Prepares to Set Up More Private EPZs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has made progress in
preparations for setting up two more private export processing
zones (EPZs) in two southeastern districts.
</P>
<P>
The preparation work is going on as two out of seven
applications by the intending developers are in the final stage of
scrutiny by the government, official and business sources said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Final clearance to the applications for developing EPZs in
Chittagong and Comilla districts, 240 and 90 kilometers southeast
of Dhaka respectively, would be given early next year.
</P>
<P>
The new Chittagong EPZ would be developed initially on 106.50
acres (43.1 hectares) of land, which would later be expanded to
500 acres (202.3 hectares), and there would be 400 plots for
industries with an estimated investment of 120 million US dollars
</P>
<P>
An estimated amount of 16 billion taka (353.6 million dollars)
would be invested to develop the Comilla EPZ on 1,500 acres (607
hectares) of land, and it would have 313 industrial plots.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are two government-run EPZs operating in
Dhaka and Chittagong.  
</P>
