<HEADLINE> S'pore Holds Condolence Service for Air Crash Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong called on all Singaporeans to be strong and live
tomorrow bravely on Tuesday at a national condolence service for
the 104 victims of the crashed SilkAir flight MI185.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the Prime Minister said, "Singapore is a small
place and a close-knit community. When a tragedy happens with a
loss of lives, it saddens the whole nation."
</P>
<P>
But, "We have to be strong. Life must go on from here, however
difficult it may be. The families must over time step out from the
sudden darkness in their lives. SilkAir must fly again with
confidence, and the country must emerge with fortitude from this
shared grief," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 8,000 people, including diplomats from the countries and
regions of the non-Singaporean victims on board flight MI185,
attended the service. Of the 104 victims, 58 were from Indonesia,
Malaysia, the United States, France, Germany, Britain, Japan,
Bosnia, Austria, Australia, India, New Zealand, and Taiwan. The
other 46 were Singaporeans.
</P>
<P>
SilkAir is a Singapore Airlines subsidiary which specializes in
regional flights. Its flight MI185 crashed into the Musi River
near Palembang, Indonesia, en route from Jakarta back to Singapore
on December 19, killing all the 97 passengers and seven crew
members on board.
</P>
<P>
After the condolence service, held in the Singapore Indoor
Stadium, was over, Singaporeans continued to come and laid flowers
and wreaths outside the Stadium for victims of the crash, the
first ever happened in the civil aviation history of Singapore.
</P>
</TEXT>
