<HEADLINE> Transport Sector Sees Fiercer Competition in 1997 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China's trains carried a total
of 916 million travelers in 1997, a decrease of 2.8 percent from
that of last year, which means another setback for China's railway
transport.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of travelers transported through highway
rose by 3.4 percent to reach 11.6 billion, and that of air
travelers, up 10.4 percent, to stand at 59 million, said an
official from transport departments under the Ministry of Railways
today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that over the decade from 1987 to 1996, the
market shares of railway, highway, and civil aviation have changed
from 54, 39, 3 percent to 39, 51, and 8 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to boost the sluggish railway transport
business, the Ministry of Railways started a nationwide move to
raise the speed of trains on April 1 this year. On some trunk
lines linking up such large cities as Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou and Harbin, the train speed reached 140 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Train's national average speed, however, still stands at over
60 kilometers per hour, far below the international normal
standard, said Tong Anyan, deputy director of the ministry's
Department of Transport.
</P>
<P>
And it is known to all that the service from Chinese train
attendants were far from "satisfactory" for a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more travelers still turned to air or bus for
their faster or more comfortable service.
</P>
<P>
Transport competition mainly lies between railway and highway,
as most people cannot afford air travel, though the means is most
ideal. Statistics show that by now, only 20 percent of the air
travelers are at their own expense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Rules out Civil Trial of Coup Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Suspects of Nigeria's foiled
coup bid announced last week would not be tried in civil courts
despite calls from some people and such countries as Britain and
the United States, according to a state administrator.
</P>
<P>
Although justice would be done, the nature of military trials
was something subject to adjudication, said Navy Commander
Anthony Onyearugbulem, Administrator of Ondo State, south
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"Military justice system has its own technicalities and its
way of doing things," the navy commander told a group of
traditional rulers Monday.
</P>
<P>
He restated that the crackdown on coup suspects had no tribal
or ethnic undertone, although some people were "trying to
ethnicize it".
</P>
<P>
"The best thing to do right now is to watch and pray that
mercy would prevail," he said, quoted by the Guardian newspaper
today.
</P>
<P>
Noting that no amount of newspaper write-ups or commentaries
would stop the military from taking military action on the issue,
the commander warned that meddling by civilians in a matter they
"know nothing about" would only complicate matters.
</P>
<P>
The remarks of the navy commander coincided with an
announcement of the military Monday that a 12-man special panel
had been set up to ascertain the involvement of those arrested
over the December 21 coup plot.
</P>
<P>
The country's number two person, chief of general staff
Lt.-gen. Oladipo Diya and 11 others are being held for the coup
attempt, which the head of state general Sani Abacha said would
erase the gains of his administration and destroyed the country's
external image, had it succeeded.
</P>
<P>
The special panel, made of members drawn from the army, navy,
air force, police and the state security service, has one month
to complete its investigation on the basis of the just concluded
preliminary investigation.
</P>
<P>
In the military, all cases, including alleged coups, are first
handled through preliminary investigations, followed by further
investigations by a special board.
</P>
<P>
Thereafter, the case is transferred to a general court martial
or a special military tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Some human rights and interests groups have called on the
military government to bring the case of coup plot to open and
fair trial. The demand is echoed by such countries as Britain and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the show of solidarity with the government has been
continuing in some places of the country, providing opportunities
to state administrators and other officials to reaffirm that the
botched coup attempt is real.
</P>
<P>
According to Information and Culture Minister Chief Ikedeasi
Mokelu, the government is in control of the situation in the
country and the alleged coup plot will not affect the
government's determination to hand over the civil rule by October
next year.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Abuja Sunday, the minister appealed
to Nigerians to remain calm, confident and committed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
