<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voting Continues in Kenya with High Turn-out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of
Kenyans have to cast their ballots today after poor organization
forced an unexpected one-day extension of the country's second
multi-party general elections due to end Monday.
</P>
<P>
Despite common complaints, Kenyans show impressive and serious
enthusiasm for choosing leaders who they believe can be the best
to head the country into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Turn-out of voters were reportedly high across Kenya with long
queues each formed by hundreds of people seen outside numerous
polling stations.
</P>
<P>
In Kisii in southwestern Kenya, voters came to polling
stations as early as 5:00 this morning and many of them had even
camped overnight outside polling stations, said local media
reports.
</P>
<P>
In Mombasa, the capital city of Coast Province, a 30-minute
downpour drenched voters queuing patiently Monday morning, but
none took shelter.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of voters went out Monday even before daybreak and
had waited for hours before their turn.
</P>
<P>
Order and peace were seen during the exercise at most polling
stations, said sources from the Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
But unconfirmed local reports said today that two to three
people were killed with dozens injured on the election day
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Transport difficulties caused by bad weather, mixed ballot
papers, missing electors names from registers, lack of ballot
papers and other technical problems also caused delays, chaos and
tension nationwide in the elections, local media said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9,031,141 registered Kenyan voters were expected to
to elect one president, 210 parliamentary members and 2,955 local
councillors for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Pre-elections opinion polls show that President Daniel arap
Moi, 73 and in power for 19 years, would take the first place
with votes ranging from 40.2 percent to 49.2 percent, almost
doubling his closest challenger Mwai Kibaki, the Democratic Party
Chairman.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's law, the winning presidential candidate must
garner the highest total and collect at least 25 percent of the
votes in at least five of Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
There are 883 candidates from 23 parties running for the
parliamentary seats while 8,446 for civic positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
