<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Attempts to Create "Two Chinas" Doomed to Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The establishment of
Sino-South African diplomatic relations once again testifies to
the fact that any attempt by Taiwan authorities to create "two
Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" is unpopular and runs counter
to the historical trend.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question concerning existing "diplomatic
relations" between Taiwan and some countries, Chinese Foreign
Ministry spokesman Tang Guoqiang said there "is no way out for the
elastic and pragmatic diplomacy" pursued by Taiwan authorities.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted, however, that some African countries still maintain
"diplomatic relations" with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He urged said countries to remain alert to any political
attempts and "clearly understand the nature of attempts by Taiwan
authorities." He noted they should proceed in the fundamental
interests of their people, and make wise decisions at an early
date.
</P>
<P>
Tang pointed out that China and African countries belong to the
developing world, share similiar historical experiences in terms
of suffering, and are faced with the common task of building their
respective countries.
</P>
<P>
No conflicts exist in terms the fundamental interests of China
and Africa, but both do share extensive common interests,
according to Tang. He added that China has always cherished
friendship with African countries and is willing to develop normal
relations and cooperation with all African nations.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan authorities have tried very hard to spread "pragmatic
diplomacy" in the international community in recent years, and
they have, in fact, used temporary economic difficulties in some
African countries to establish or rebuild "diplomatic ties" under
the guise of providing economic assistance, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
The true intent of Taiwan authorities is not to help African
countries, but instead to use economic means to undermine
traditional friendship between China and the African nations, he
said, adding that Taiwan buys diplomatic recognition, attempts to
create "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" and splits its own
country," said Tang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Draws Policy to Develop Inland Waterways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 30 (Xinhua)-- The government is drawing a
blueprint to substantially increase goods traffic through inland
waterways and a policy on private participation in the sector will
be finalized soon, said Surface Transport Secretary Yogendra
Narain here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 13th annual general meeting of the Overseas
Construction Council of India (OCCI), he said that the government
is considering to adopt regulatory measures to promote movement of
fertilizers, coal, cement, crude oil and petroleum products, and
steel through this mode and decongest the traffic by road and
rail. So far three national waterways are in the process of being
developed. The inland waterways sector would be handling about 20
million tones of freight by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The government is targeting to double port capacity in India to
handle 424 million tones by the end of the Ninth Five Year plan
period (1998-2002) from the present 214 million tones. A number of
measures to augment port capacity and improve efficiency through
joint ventures between major ports and private sector are on the
anvil, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
