<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The traditional bout of
window dressing by institutional investors left the stock market
higher at the close Tuesday in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed up 25.1 points, or 0.97
percent, at 2601.4 as institutions sought to finish the year on a
high note.
</P>
<P>
The local bourse was also boosted, mainly by the US and most
European markets. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones Industrial Average
gained 113.10 points to finish at 7,792.41.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials closed up 41.0 points, or 0.93 percent, at
4447.0 while the all resources closed up 12.7 points, or 1.14
percent, at 1130.7.
</P>
<P>
The only weak spot among the sectors was gold, where a fall in
the price of gold bullion dragged down share prices. The index
finished Tuesday down 19.0, or 1.86 percent, at 1005.1 points.
</P>
<P>
Gold closed in Sydney at 291.10 US dollars, having dropped
earlier to 289.60 US dollars, compared to a close in Sydney Monday
at 293.70 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australia's biggest gold producer, Normandy, lost three
Australian cents to close at 1.46 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the major resource stocks, market leader BHP gained 20.7
cents to close at 14.36 Australian dollars, and Rio Tinto surged
49 cents to 17.69 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks provided some of the biggest gains among the all
industrials with National Australia Bank rising 42 cents to 21.394
Australian dollars. Commonwealth Bank gained 11 cents to close at
17.60 Australian dollars, Westpac gained five to 9.80 Australian
dollars and ANZ bank rose 17 to 9.82 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australian telecommunications giant Telstra installment
receipts remained the most heavily traded securities, with 22.791
million lots changing hands. Their price fell two cents to 3.16
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall, national turnover was 199 million shares, valued at
393.36 million with rises outnumbering falls 592 to 340.  
</P>
