<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
weakened after gold prices slipped Monday.
</P>
<P>
Also, traders cited end-of-year book-squaring by participants
on the last full day of trading for 1997 as adding to the markets'
slightly negative tone.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 65.48 US cents, down from 65.78
late Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gold in Sydney closed at 291.10 US dollars per fine ounce, down
from 293.70 US dollars Monday.
</P>
<P>
Traders also said an illiquid market in holiday mode before the
New Year break was more susceptible to swings in value.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank Manager of Foreign Exchange Trading Stuart Moore
said thin volumes moved the Australian dollar further than normal,
as traders moved to square up their end of year positions.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank chief economist Craig James said the
Australian dollar was likely to be mired around 0.6500 US dollars
to 0.6700 dollars for a number of months given the poor outlook
for the Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
James said the Asian crisis acted as a "double whammy" for
Australia, impacting severely on exports to the region and world
commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
He said over the past four months the Australian dollar had
fallen just over 12 percent against the American dollar, while
commodity prices had dropped almost 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"How much of a surprise is the Australian dollar at 65 US cents
when gold is just above 18 year lows, copper prices are at four
year lows, oil prices are near 2 year lows and aluminum prices are
near 12 month lows," James said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished the session at 85.05 yen, from
85.56 Monday, and at 1.1706 marks, from 1.1651.  
</P>
</TEXT>
