<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Active Non-governmental Exchanges in 1997 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China has actively carried out
non-governmental contacts during 1997 in support of its fruitful
achievements in foreign diplomacy, according to a senior Chinese
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
In an article carried in today's People's Daily, Qi Huaiyuan,
president of the Chinese People's Association for Friendship with
Foreign Countries (CPAFFC), China's major organization engaged in
non-governmental exchanges, reviewed the association's activities
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
According to Qi, the association hosted over 200 delegations
from more than 50 countries and regions in 1997, including 30
delegations consisting of either prominent political figures or
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the association maintained contacts with over 260
organizations and social institutions in 100-odd countries.
</P>
<P>
The CPAFFC hosted delegations from friendship organizations in
over 30 countries, and sent delegations to more than 40 countries.
</P>
<P>
Qi said that maintaining communications with countries which
have not as yet established diplomatic relations with China
constitutes an important part of the association's job. He
specifically cited visits by delegations from South Africa and
other nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
