<HEADLINE> New Budget to Reflate Nigerian Economy, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's newly-inauguarated
cabinet is in its second-day deliberations on the 1998 budget
today for expected ratification by the supreme provisional ruling
council tomorrow, the Vanguard reported.
</P>
<P>
Henceforth, the new budget will be announced not later than
January 3, said National Planning Minister Chief Ayo Ogunlade at
the end of the five-hour cabinet meeting in the capital Abuja
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the thrust of the budget will include
consolidating gains, reflating the economy, increase in capacity
utilization of industry, easy import of goods by manufacturers
and attractive atmosphere for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
While the salaries of public servants will be increased, the
budget will also affect the generality of Nigerians for
confidence building, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister hinted that the government was poised to scrap
the dual exchange rate, noting that "the mistake we have been
making is that there are two exchange rates, whereas the 22 naira
to the dollar is merely an accounting and a book keeping
strategy".
</P>
<P>
But he did not explain why it has been so.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the macroeconomic success, the minister said the
economy had been turned around from 103 billion naira deficit
recorded in December 1993 to 36 billion naira surplus last year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that inflation rate had also dropped from 77.8
percent in January 1995 to below 10 percent currently.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Finance Minister Chief Anthony Ani promised that the
new budget would be read on December 31.
</P>
<P>
If the budget is released on or before January 3, it would be
the earliest time that the government will unveil the budget.
</P>
<P>
This year's budget was read on January 18. Last year, it was ready
much later, and ditto the 1995 and 1994 budgets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
