<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministry Spokesman on Sino-South African Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese and South African
governments will sign a series of bilateral agreements following
the establishment of diplomatic ties on January 1, 1998, in order
to promote the development of the economic cooperation and trade
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The agreements will guarantee trade between the two
countries," Tang Guoqiang, spokesman for the Chinese Foreign
Ministry, said at today's regular press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will also encourage businesses in the
two countries to initiate various forms of cooperation and explore
potential avenues for cooperation in wide-ranging fields,
according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Sino-South African economic cooperation and trade
will witness great advancement following the establishment of
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
China, the largest developing country in the world, and South
Africa, the most developed country in Africa, have their own
features and experience in economic development, as well as in
science, technology and culture, said Tang, adding that the two
countries can learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
China can supply South Africa with food products, edible oil,
machinery and electronics products, building materials, steel,
telecommunications equipment and chemicals, and South Africa's
abundant mineral resources can cater to market demand in China,
said Tang.
</P>
<P>
"Practice over the past several years have proved the
complementary aspects of the economies of China and South Africa,"
according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is China's largest trade partner in Africa, with
the trade volume between the two growing to 1.3 billion US dollars
in 1996 from only 10 million US dollars in 1992. The 1997 volume
is expected to reach 1.6 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
