<HEADLINE> France Urges Congo Republic to Resume Dialogue With Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- New ambassador of France to
the Congo Republic, Herve Bolot, urged Tuesday the government of
General Denis Sassou Nguesso to resume dialogue with donor
countries on aid programs, reported Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Bolot, who presented the credentials to Sassou Nguesso on
Monday, told AFP that France is ready to support Brazzaville in
its "effort of dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The toppled president of Congo, Pascal Lissouba, had concluded
an agreement with donor countries on economic structural
readjustment, whose implementation was interrupted by a five-month
civil conflict between the forces of Lissouba and Sassou Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
During a private visit to Paris last week, Sassou Nguesso
talked with President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin on issues of financial aid by France and the normalization
of political situation in his country through a presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
But Brazzaville has not publicly announced its need for
financial aid to reconstruct the country following the war, in
which between 4,000 and 10,000 people were killed and the capital
Brazzaville seriously damaged. 
</P>
