<HEADLINE> China, S. Africa Sign Documents over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China and South Africa
today signed a join communique over the establishment of
diplomatic relations between the two countries and other five
governmental documents ranging from diplomacy to cooperation in
economic and investment fields.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
and South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo signed the joint
communique, which will be effective on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Deputy Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation Shi Guangsheng and South African Deputy Foreign
Minister Aziz Pahad participated in the ceremony and signed a
part of cooperation documents on behalf of their respective
governments.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest agreements, South Africa will maintain its
Consulate General in Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of
the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had set up its Consulate General in Hong Kong
before Hong Kong was returned to China on July 1 this year. The
two governments agreed at the time that South Africa's Consulate
General in Hong Kong could keep operation until December 31, 1997
as a temporary arrangement.
</P>
<P>
In terms of agreements between the two countries, China and
South Africa have agreed to the reciprocal encouragement and
protection of investment and to the mutual establishment of
consulates in each other's cities.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese consulates in South Africa will be separately
located in Johannesburg, Cape Town and Durban while South Africa
will have a consulate in Shanghai, China.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached an agreement to the temporary
arrangements for the overflight of the territorial airspace of
China by South African airlines for regular air service.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese government also agreed to offer grant
to the South African government.
</P>
<P>
Qian arrived in South Africa for a five-day official visit at
the invitation of Nzo. He is due to attend the opening ceremony
of the Chinese Embassy in Pretoria, the administrative capital of
South Africa, on January 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
