<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli industrial imports and exports rose in
October and November, the Jerusalem Post today quoted a report of
the Central Statistics Bureau as reporting.
</P>
<P>
In November alone, industrial imports rose 16 percent and
industrial exports, excluding diamonds, rose 7 percent, similar to
the increases in September and October, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli agricultural revenues will register a 26
percent drop for the whole year of 1997 to 1.6 billion shekels
(457 million U.S. dollars), latest official figures show.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Ministry said this is compared to the 20
percent fall in 1996. It attributed the drop to several factors,
including a drought in the South that damaged the fields as well
as the damage fruit crops sustained in the North.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The investment in Israel's infrastructure in the
next five years will amount to 15 billion U.S. dollars, according
to a report of the Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted some Israeli economists as saying that more
than half of the sum would be invested in developing the
electricity infrastructure. And investments in transportation are
expected to total 3.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- The Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OAPEC) has predicted that the world demand for oil
would increase by about 1.8 million barrels per day (bpd) next year.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of a monthly bulletin of the OAPEC estimated
that world demand for oil in 1998 in developing countries would
increase by 1.2 million bpd to reach 21.9 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Oil demand among the industrial countries would also increase
by about half a million bpd next year and in the central Asian
countries, by about 100,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) has regained its
position as the No. 1 oil supplier to Japan in November, after
briefly yielding the position to Saudi Arabia in October.
</P>
<P>
Japan imported roughly 6.54 million kiloliters of crude oil
from the UAE last month, up 12 percent from 5.84 million
kiloliters in October, latest official figures show.
</P>
<P>
Japan's crude oil imports from Saudi Arabia amounted to 4.95
million kiloliters in November, down 24.5 percent from 6.56
million kiloliters the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources in UAE's oil sector said that the UAE is
expected to step up its sales drives to Japan after the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) decided to
raise the group's production to 27.5 million bpd at its latest
conference held in Indonesia between November 26 and December 1.
</P>
<P>
As a major OPEC member, the UAE raised its quota from some 2.3
million bpd to 2.5 million bpd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
