<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramadan Starts In Egypt Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today kicked off the
Islamic Holy month of fasting with a full-range of cultural and
religious festivities as well as public care for the needy.
</P>
<P>
The sighting of the Crescent, which determines the start of
Ramadan, was announced Monday night by Farid Mohammed Wasel,
Egypt's mufti, the country's highest Islamic religious authority.
</P>
<P>
A number of Arab states, including Saudi Arabia, Qatar,
Bahrain, Yemen and Lebanon also declared that Ramadan began from
today, according to the Middle East News Agency. But Iraq said it
will observe the holy month from Wednesday according to the
emergence of the crescent.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan is the ninth month of the Islamic lunar year, observed
as sacred with abstaining from food, drink, smoke and sex from
dawn to dusk. It is the month when Koran, the Islamic holy book,
was revealed to Prophet Mohammed 1,400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim fasting month has special importance for the one
billion Muslims worldwide not only because of its religious
importance but also because it includes the largest amount of
religious, cultural and even artistic activities.
</P>
<P>
Apart from short working hours, Cairo streets and public
districts in Ramadan can be another attractive item with
glittering festoons and lamps hanging on the shop-fronts and swarms
of people enjoying charity food in open air.
</P>
<P>
Religious seminars, cultural soirees and folk art performances
will be held during the month in different state-owned theaters
and palaces of culture. They will attract large audiences.
</P>
<P>
This year, the Opera House in Cairo, responsible for art
performance during the holy month, has decided to hold a series of
religious lectures and host folk art troupes and music ensembles
from other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The majority of students, however, will not be able to fully
enjoy the festivities of the Ramadan as it coincides with mid-term
exams at schools and universities.
</P>
<P>
Along with the many cultural and entertainment activities, many
people are already relishing the prospect of having an Iftar, the
breakfast ending a day's fasting at sunset and a Sorour, the
banquet before sunrise.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan is also the time for the poor and the unfortunate to
enjoy charity food as the rich and public institutions set up
their charity meal stalls throughout the country during the month.
</P>
<P>
To spice up the atmosphere of festivity and encourage shopping,
the government has decided to move ahead to mid-January the spring
sales season, which used to come after Ramadan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stamps Commemorating Diana to Be Issued in U.K. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- British Royal Mail stamps
commemorating Diana, Princess of Wales, are to go on sale at the
beginning of February.
</P>
