<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Hong Kong Stands Test of Asian Financial Storm (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A few months after returning
to China, Hong Kong was confronted with a regional currency
turmoil but has so far seemed to be able to weather the regional
instability.
</P>
<P>
As international speculation triggered falling dominoes among
Asian currencies over the past few months, the peg between the
Hong Kong dollar and the greenback has stood firm at one
U.S. dollar to 7.8 HK dollars, the benchmark set in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Faced with a wave of speculative attacks on the local currency,
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government
resolved to defend the link and, with resources and skill, has
succeeded in fending off the speculators.
</P>
<P>
The government's strong fiscal position has made Hong Kong
well-positioned against external shocks. The city with a
population of 6.3 million has the world's third largest foreign
reserves, measured at 91.8 billion U.S. dollars at the end of
October. It has no single cent of foreign debt thanks to a prudent
fiscal policy, which restrains the growth of government
expenditure well below the GDP (gross domestic product) growth.
</P>
<P>
Certainly, the peg was kept with a price. Overnight interbank
lending rate at one moment hit 300 percent in reaction to
speculative attacks in late October, and the jacked-up three-month
rate is now still hovering around 10 percent, putting strains on
all borrowers.
</P>
<P>
"In keeping the peg, merits outweigh demerits," said Professor
Y.C. Jao at the School of Economics and Finance, University of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The short-term pain caused by higher interest rates, most
notably the plunges in stock and property prices, was the lesser
of the two evils, compared with financial uncertainty and loss of
confidence that could be triggered by the disassociation of the
link, he argued.
</P>
<P>
Despite the predicted shrinking profits as a result of soaring
interest rates in the last quarter of 1997, Hong Kong's banking
sector remains healthy and well-capitalized. The capital adequacy
ratio for locally-incorporated banks stood impressively at 17.8
percent, far exceeding the 8 percent statutory requirement under
the Basic Capital Rules to be one of the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
A minor run on the International Bank of Asia in early November
was quenched in a day or two, demonstrative the high liquidity
levels held by local banks have made them well prepared for a
sudden wave of customer withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), which has consistently
kept a close watch on the banking system, began in early November
to step up its inspection of local banks on a daily basis to
ensure it is able to react rapidly to any financial jitters.
</P>
<P>
In December, the Washington-based think-tank Heritage
Foundation confirmed in its study that "Hong Kong is a world
banking center and one of the world's most stable banking
environment."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Hong Kong Stands Test of Asian Financial Storm (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an increasingly integrated global financial market, Hong
Kong is not immune from the regional currency turmoil, which
originated in Thailand in early July, spilled over to other
Southeast Asian economies, and recently spread to the Republic of
Korea (ROK) and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index, the barometer which traces the performance
of 33 blue-chips listed on the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong (SEHK),
plummeted 1,211 points on October 23, the biggest single-day point
loss in history. Riding on the roller-coaster, Hong Kong stock
prices went down from a peak of 16,673 points in August to around
the 10,000-point level these days.
</P>
<P>
Against the depressing scene, Edgar Cheng, former chairman of
the SEHK, still saw the underlying strength. He said: "One
noteworthy aspect is that our market systems have withstood
dramatic swings in stock prices and heavy trading volume without
any sign of strain."
</P>
<P>
In late October when all major stock markets around the globe
experienced sharp falls, the Hong Kong market remained firmly
open and continued to operate in an orderly manner, reflecting its
state of maturity.
</P>
<P>
In his view, the recent market turmoil would neither alter the
long-term trend of increasing investment in Asia by global
investors, nor reduce the huge demand for capital by Asian
economies, especially China which is determined to reform its
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent financial uncertainty, Hong Kong for the
fourth year in a row was rated by the Heritage Foundation as the
freest economy in the world.
</P>
<P>
With little government interference in the marketplace and a
high degree of economic freedom, Hong Kong not only tops the
foundation's scoreboard of 156 economies across the world, but has
a remarkable ability to weather tough times.
</P>
<P>
David Dodwell, co-author of the influential book "Hong Kong
Advantage", said: "It (the Asian financial turmoil) is a valuable
test of the strength of Hong Kong. Hong Kong has very effectively,
efficiently mediated the challenges that swept over it through
October."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Hong Kong's intrinsic strength lies in its
immense flexibility and a wide spectrum of economic activities and
markets.
</P>
<P>
Dodwell believed that a quick adaptation to the changing
environment has helped and will continue to help Hong Kong recover
rapidly in the wake of crisis.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Hong kong is luckily placed to have good strong
business links with the Chinese mainland to give it an extra area
of business activities to keep the economy robust, he added.
</P>
<P>
As Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Special Administrative
Region (SAR) put it in Vancouver last month, Hong Kong, given its
sound fundamentals, robust monetary and banking systems, huge
foreign reserves, flexibility and resilience in coping with
external shocks, would be the first economy to rebound after the
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Plans to Reshuffle PNA Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat has promised to reshuffle
the PNA cabinet in the near future, Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center (JMCC) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen PNA cabinet ministers, including Agriculture Minister
Abdul Jawad Saleh, submitted their resignations to Arafat on
August 1 this years. And Arafat has not made his final decision on
the cabinet reshuffle till now, JMCC said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was quoted as saying Monday that the Authority would
function as a transition government for another month and a half,
pending a reshuffle of portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also agreed to set up a committee to include Fatah (main
stream Faction of the Palestine Liberation Organization) members to
discuss the reshuffle, it said.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts between the Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC) and
the PNA Executive Authority have been intensified
recently. Several PLC members openly accused some cabinet
ministers of having both a poor performance of work and records of
corruptions.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the PLC's session was adjourned after some of its
members warned to introduce a no-confidence motion against the
cabinet if the Executive Authority did not not approve laws
adopted by the PLC.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Arafat held an urgent meeting in Ramallah with the
Fatah PLC members and discussed the relation between the PLC and
the Executive Authority.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Arafat stressed that the present government
is a temporary one and that he intends to make some cabinet
changes in the near future, probably after his return from his
meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington next month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat also instructed the PNA legislation department
to speed up the preparations on a number of legislations for
his approval, as part of the PNA plan for administrative
reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
