<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, S. Africa Sign Communique on Diplomatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China and South Africa today
signed a joint communique, agreeing to establish diplomatic
relations at ambassadorial level as from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed in Pretoria by Chinese Vice-Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo.
</P>
<P>
"The Government of the People's Republic of China and the
Government of the Republic of South Africa, in conformity with
the interests and desire of the two peoples, have decided upon
mutual recognition and the establishment of diplomatic relations
at ambassadorial level as from January 1, 1998," the communique
reads.
</P>
<P>
"The Government of the Republic of South Africa recognizes
that there is but one China in the world, the Government of the
People's Republic of China is the sole legal government
representing the whole of China, and recognizes China's position
that Taiwan is an inalienable part of China."
</P>
<P>
The two governments also agreed to exchange ambassadors as
soon as possible, and to develop friendly relations and
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said after talks with
Qian in Cape Town Monday that it was in the interests of South
Africa to have diplomatic relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived in South Africa Sunday for a five-day
official visit, has met National Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala
and Tokyo Sexwale, premier of Gauteng Province.
</P>
<P>
Qian is also scheduled to open the Chinese Embassy in Pretoria
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela declared in November 1996 that his country would sever
ties with Taiwan and establish diplomatic relations with the
People's Republic of China by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
China and South Africa established study centers in each
other's capitals in February 1992 under agreements reached in
November 1991.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries witnessed rapid growth in
recent years with the bilateral trade in 1996 jumping to 1.35
billion U.S. Dollars from mere 14 million dollars in 1991. It is
expected to exceed 1.5 billion dollars this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-South African Relations Reach A Milestone (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ji said that Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen's ongoing official visit to South Africa, which commenced
on December 28, represents a major event in the bilateral
relationship.
</P>
<P>
He said the joint communique signed by the two sides on the
establishment of diplomatic relations has completed the legal
procedures for the normalization of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian's visit will include wide-ranging exchanges of view with
South African leaders on the further development of bilateral
relations and other issues of common concern, Ji said, adding that
the two nations will also sign a number of cooperative agreements.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Qian's visit will deepen mutual understanding and
friendship, and will usher in a new chapter of friendship and
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ji said that the formal establishment of diplomatic relations
will create conditions necessary for high-level exchange
visits. "We believe the two sides will engage in more exchanges,
including more high-level exchange of visits between the two
countries," said Ji.
</P>
