<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-South African Relations Reach A Milestone (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing the question why China and South Africa failed to
establish diplomatic relations for such a long period of time, Ji
noted that the Chinese government and people have firmly supported
the people of South Africa in their struggle for racial equality
and have, in turn, sealed a time-honored friendship. He also
pointed to the fact that people in South Africa have deep feelings
for Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two countries did not establish diplomatic
relations soon after the birth of the new South Africa because of
that nation's "diplomatic relations" with Taiwan which was left
over from the period of apartheid. The government of the new South
Africa needed time to deal with said relations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government expressed understanding that the
government of the new South Africa required some time to readjust
its relations with China, said Ji.
</P>
<P>
Ji referred to factors which promoted the establishment of
diplomatic relations by noting that China is the largest
developing country in the world and a permanent member of the
United Nations Security Council, while South Africa is one of the
largest nations in Africa and an important member in the group of
developing countries and the nonaligned movement.
</P>
<P>
The two countries witnessed the same historical suffering and
face similar tasks, said Ji, adding that broad prospects exist for
bilateral political, diplomatic, economic, trade, scientific and
technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the two countries should engage in close
consultations in major international and regional issues. "These
are major factors which have promoted the establishment of
diplomatic relations," noted Ji.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-South African Relations Reach A Milestone (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With regard to bilateral economic and trade cooperation, Ji
said that unofficial economic and trade relations between the two
countries have developed rapidly in recent years, despite the lack
of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the bilateral trade volume for 1991 stood at 14
million US dollars, with the figure soaring to 1.34 billion US
dollars in 1996. This year's trade volume is expected to reach
1.6 billion US dollars, said Ji, adding that Chinese enterprises
have invested more than 100 million US dollars in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ji pointed to the fact that the two nations share highly
complimentary economies which offer vast potential for bilateral
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ji also noted that companies and enterprises in the two
countries are keenly interested in economic and trade cooperation,
and are rapidly expanding direct links.
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of diplomatic relations will provide
further political guarantees for bilateral economic and trade
exchanges. Ji also noted that the Chinese government will
encourage financially sound Chinese enterprises to invest in South
Africa and engage in mutually beneficial cooperation. He added
that the prospects for bilateral economic and trade cooperation
will expand even further with the establishment of diplomatic
ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
