<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-South African Relations Reach A Milestone (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ji noted that China and South Africa are developing countries
which share many fundamental interests and play important roles in
their respective regions.
</P>
<P>
He noted the two nations have identical viewpoints on many
major international issues, and added that strengthening bilateral
consultations and cooperation in international affairs will enable
them to play an even greater role on international arena and
safeguard the legal rights and interests of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The two economies have different characteristics and respective
advantages in terms of resources, said Ji. However, historical
factors limited exchanges and resulted in a lack of mutual
understanding.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of diplomatic relations will enable China and
South Africa to learn from each other in their respective nation
reconstruction, said Ji.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, according to Ji, the normalization of relations
will serve the fundamental interests of the two peoples, and will
further promote the development of friendship and cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ji said that promotion of solidarity and cooperation between
China and African nations, as well as developing countries as a
whole, represents an important part of China's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
China is fully prepared to work with African nations to develop
a long-term and stable Sino-African relationship based on
all-round cooperation and oriented toward the 21st century, said
Ji.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the fact that South Africa, an important nation
on the African continent, works to promote regional peace and
development and plays an active role in both African and
international affairs. He added that South Africa currently chairs
both the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development and
the Southern African Development Community, and will chair the
nonaligned movement in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ji said the normalization of relations between the two
countries will usher in a new chapter of bilateral relations and
will promote unity and cooperation between China and African
nations, as well as developing countries as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, according to Ji, the strengthening of solidarity
and cooperation amongst developing countries will give a powerful
push to the formation of a multi-polar world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
