<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Presses Ahead in 1997 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese economy has drawn
the world attention with its favorable growth momentum in 1997, in
sharp contrast to the dim future for other emerging Asian
economies plagued by financial storms.
</P>
<P>
Its superb performance has won almost unanimous high praise,
either in the analytical reports of international authoritative
institutions such as the International Monetary Fund (IMF), or
from ranking officials of other countries.
</P>
<P>
This provided a solid basis for a general and consistent
confidence in China's future, despite the death early this year of
Deng Xiaoping, the chief architect of the country's reform and
opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that China registered an economic growth
rate of 8.8 percent this year, with the inflation rate dropped to
0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists hailed it as a miracle that the Chinese government
could achieve high economic growth in tandem with such low
inflation, as the Chinese economy was plagued by a runaway
inflation of 21.7 percent just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the overheated economy has since steadily cooled down,
as a result of the nation's effective control measures over real
estate speculations, the top blame for the "bubble economy".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thanks to the proposition and guidances of President
Jiang Zemin and other senior leaders, disputes calmed down and the
consensus was reached to boldly utilize management mode and form
of assets ownership, including the joint-stock form, that complies
with the law of what guiding social production.
</P>
<P>
As an immediate outcome, China's state-owned enterprise reform
entered upon a new era: the pace for merging, acquisition and
restructuring of the large- and medium-sized state firms are
reported to have accelerated over recent months.
</P>
<P>
And the total profits from the state-owned sector is expected
to post double-digit annual growth this year over 1996, although
it still takes time for the sector to move out of the financial
dilemma, according to officials with the State Economic and Trade
Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Presses Ahead in 1997  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In analyzing the prospects for China's economic growth,
economists referred to its huge market potential and growing
export demand as the two other factors that props the Chinese
economy.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Dam, as the world's largest water conservation
scheme, best indicated the infinite market opportunities in
China. With an estimated cost of a total of 200 billion yuan upon
completion in 2009, it already induced a group of multinationals
to vie with each other for the project's international orders.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 70 percent of the equipment used in the
project have been purchased overseas.
</P>
<P>
China's efforts to reduce its foreign trade barrier also won
the acclamation from the international community. Following the
recent slash of the tariff level to 17 percent in October, China
committed itself to further tariff reduction up to the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
All these have contributed greatly to a general optimism of the
international investors toward the nation's economic future. China
is estimated to have drawn record 62 billion US dollars in direct
foreign investment this year, against the backdrop of investment
withdrawal from some Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
As for the export traders, they posted a trade surplus of about
40 billion US dollars this year, despite the mounting pressure
from the currency depreciation of other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, along with a steadily increasing foreign exchange
reserve, the Renminbi steadily gained value against the greenback
this year, indicating the steady manner the Chinese government has
adopted in the course of its opening-up.
</P>
<P>
As the IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus has noted, it is
impressive that the Chinese can keep a fast economic growth while
avoiding economic instability, and attract foreign investment in
large quantities.
</P>
<P>
His view was echoed by Bill Gates, the Microsoft Executive
General during his recent fifth visit to China, who pointed to the
the nation's infinite market opportunities and expressed his fully
confidence in further increasing cooperations with the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
