<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: New Era in China-South Africa Relations (1) by Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited normalization
of relations between China and South Africa was realized today in
Pretoria, South Africa, when the foreign ministers of the two
countries signed a joint communique on full diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
The event, an important link in the chain of China's diplomatic
activities, took place during Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen's ongoing visit to South Africa, and completes China's
diplomatic agenda for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the establishment of diplomatic
relations between the two nations marks a new beginning of
development in bilateral ties, and will have a positive impact on
expanding cooperation between China and African countries and
other developing countries, as well as on establishing a fair and
reasonable new international economic and political order.
</P>
<P>
They also point to the fact that forging diplomatic relations
between the two countries will promote the exchange of views
and consultations between the two countries on African affairs,
and will promote stability and development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela announced at the end of
1996 that his country would sever "diplomatic relations" with
Taiwan and establish full diplomatic ties with the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
He noted that South Africa's "diplomatic recognition" of Taiwan
is not compatible with the role his country plays in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the two countries have since engaged in
frequent exchange visits to work for the establishment of
diplomatic relations. Chinese Assistant Foreign Minister Ji
Peiding visited South Africa earler this year, and South African
Vice-Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad visited China in June.
</P>
<P>
Qian and his South African counterpart Alfred Nzo met at the
United Nations headquarters in New York in September and reached a
consensus on issues related to the normalization of diplomatic
relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-S. African Joint Communique on Diplomatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-premier and
Foreign Minister, Qian Qichen, and South African Foreign Minister
Alfred Nzo signed a joint communique in Pretoria today to
establish diplomatic relations between the two countries as from
January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The full text of the joint communique reads as follows:
</P>
<P>
Joint Communique Between The Government Of The People's
Republic Of China And The Government Of The Republic Of South
Africa On The Establishment Of Diplomatic Relations
</P>
<P>
1. The Government of the People's Republic of China and the
Government of the Republic of South Africa, in conformity with
the interests and desire of the two peoples, have decided upon
mutual recognition and the establishment of diplomatic relations
at ambassadorial level as from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
2. The Government of the People's Republic of China and the
Government of the Republic of South Africa agree to develop the
friendly relations and cooperation between the two countries on
the basis of the principles of mutual respect for sovereignty and
territorial integrity, mutual non-aggression, non-interference in
each other's internal affairs, equality and mutual benefit and
peaceful coexistence.
</P>
<P>
3. The government of the Republic of South Africa recognizes
that there is but one China in the world, the Government of the
People's Republic of China is the sole legal government
representing the whole of China and recognizes China's position
that Taiwan is an inalienable part of China.
</P>
<P>
4. The government of the People's Republic of China and the
Government of the Republic of South Africa agree, on the basis of
the principle of reciprocity and in accordance with the relevant
provisions of the Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations, to
provide each other with all the necessary assistance for the
establishment and performance of the functions of diplomatic
missions in their respective capitals and to exchange ambassadors
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen  Alfred Nzo
</P>
<P>
(Signature)  (Signature)
</P>
<P>
For the Government of  For the Government of
the People's Republic of China the Republic of South Africa
</P>
<P>
 Pretoria, December 30, 1997
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: New Era in China-South Africa Relations (2) by Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Senior South African leaders have on many occassions reiterated
that the decision to establish diplomatic relations with China is
irreversible and an inevitable choice of the South African
government.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Nzo rejected Taiwan's unreasonable requests
for negotiating future Taiwan-South Africa ties.
</P>
<P>
Nzo stated that Taiwan requests to retain its "symbols, flag
and name" and its three "consulates" in South Africa after the two
sides severed diplomatic relations do not comply with the
international law and are "untenable."
</P>
<P>
Yang Lihua, a research fellow with the Center for Southern
African Studies of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, told
Xinhua that the establishment of China-South Africa relations is
not only based on extensive and important common interests the two
sides share, but also on evaluations the two nations have made
with an eye to their future development prospects.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who has visited South Africa four times, said the
establishment of diplomatic relations represents a "common need of
both sides."
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who relinquished his ANC presidency to his successor
during the recent 50th National Congress of the South African
National Congress (ANC), noted that one of the major achievements
of the South African government over the past three years has been
to settle the issue of normalizing relations with the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
China is the largest developing country and South Africa is the
most developed nation in Africa. Differences in terms of
resources, and industrial and consumption structures point to the
complimentary nature of their economies.
</P>
<P>
China and South Africa are important trade partners, and the
two countries share enormous potential for cooperation in
high-tech sectors such as space, aviation and electronics, as well
as in other areas including the exploration, mining,
metallurgy, construction, energy and finance.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in South Africa's Business Day, the
annual trade volume between South Africa and China including Hong
Kong tops three billion US dollars, a level much higher than the
level with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the industrial and business community in
South Africa firmly support the government decision to establish
diplomatic relations with China at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
She noted that business, academic and cultural communities in
South Africa have shown an increasing interest in China and are
ready to increase exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that the consistent support of the Chinese government
and people to South African people in their just struggle against
apartheid, particularly their moral and material assistance
to the ANC in the crucial period in the 1980s, has helped to
accelerate the process of normalizing relations between the two
nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
