<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 08:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Japan to Boost Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and Japan
have agreed to step up efforts to boost bilateral economic
cooperation, Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported today from Riyadh,
the capital of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the two countries agreed to sign an investment
protection agreement during the current visit by Japanese Minister
of International Trade and Industry Horiuchi Mitsuo in Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Saudi and Japanese officials have also
succeeded in expanding "scope of understanding" and have become
more convinced of the necessity to establish a full partnership in
the economic, investment, trade, technological and technical
fields by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese minister, who arrived in Riyadh Friday, called on
Saudi Arabia to increase its participation in industrial projects
in his country, while Saudi officials expressed hope that Japan
will increase import of Saudi oil and launch joint projects in the
oil and minerals fields.
</P>
<P>
Japan currently imports 1.2 million barrels of oil per day from
Saudi Arabia and is expecting to increase the importation to 2.15
million barrels.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil producer and exporter, is
Japan's second largest oil supplier after the United Arab
Emirates. Saudi government expressed hope to Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto when he visited Riyadh in November that
Japan will increase oil imports from the world top oil producer.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese minister also conveyed a letter from Hashimoto to
King Fahd Bin Abdul-Aziz of Saudi Arabia on the willingness to
promote bilateral relations, Kuna said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Saudi sources were quoted as saying that Saudi
Arabia was looking forward to a larger cooperation convenient to
the capabilities of both states.
</P>
<P>
They said Riyadh wants Japan to expand its investments in the
Gulf state beyond the petrochemical industry, which constitutes
the core of Japan's 1.5 billion U.S. dollars investments in the
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has been complaining that Japanese investment in
the Kingdom has not been commensurate with Japan's economic
strength. 
</P>
</TEXT>
