<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Advocating Free Economic Zone in CIS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Russia is advocating the
establishment of a free economic zone in the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) area.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Cooperation with CIS Countries Anatoly Adamishin
said here Monday that this would be helpful in further promoting
the integration of CIS member nations.
</P>
<P>
Adamishin, as quoted by an Interfax news agency report, said
Russia's volume of trade with other CIS members has continued to
be on the downward slope in this out-going year.
</P>
<P>
The decline, he said, is related not only to economic problems
existing in the CIS community, but also to the fact that some of
the CIS nations levy a surtax on imports from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Trade among CIS nations could grow only if they achieve
economic stability and resolve their disputes over indirect
taxation, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the proposed free economic zone, Adamishin said the project
will lay an indispensable common ground for all CIS nations to
carry out their individual goals and to integrate the CIS.
</P>
<P>
While advocating the CIS integration, Russia is not against
diversity in the process toward that end, he said.
</P>
<P>
The integration of Russia and Belarus, and the tax union of
Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan and Kyrkyzstan are real examples of
the preserved diversity, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
