<HEADLINE> Kuwait Backs Bid to End Hardships of Iraqi People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait backs any bid to
end the hardships of the Iraqi people and does not object to Arab
delegations' visit to Iraq for humanitarian purposes, a senior
Kuwaiti official has said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency today quoted Kuwaiti Information Minister
Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah as saying after taking part in a
meeting of Kuwaiti parliamentary Foreign Affairs Committee that
"we have no problem with the Iraqi people, but our dispute with
the regime in Iraq is still standing."
</P>
<P>
In response to a call for dialogue by an Iraqi newspaper to
resolve the Iraqi-Kuwaiti differences, Sheikh Saud said "the
Iraqi regime understands that the stand of Kuwait is explicit in
this regard, as it has been a stance agreed upon at the
government and popular levels."
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that "Kuwait does not oppose to the dispatch of
Arab or foreign delegations to Iraq for humanitarian purposes to
end the hardships of the Iraqi people and offer medicines and food
with approval of the international sanctions committee of the
United Nations."
</P>
<P>
But the minister said earlier this month after the three-day
Gulf Cooperation Council summit here that Kuwait was ready for an
Arab reconciliation based on clear understanding, but ruled out
reconciliation with the Iraqi regime.
</P>
<P>
He warned against confusion in this respect as "our position
toward the Iraqi regime is out of the reconciliation issue as it
is not a Kuwaiti but an international cause."
</P>
<P>
The two countries severed diplomatic relations after Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait in 1990 which sparked off the 1991 Gulf
War. The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq in 1990 for its invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
So far, the prisoners of war and other issues have still
hindered the improvement of ties between Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
