<HEADLINE> Philippines' New Police Chief Vows to Fight Kidnappers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Newly-installed Police Director
General Santiago Alino has vowed to fight big kidnapping
syndicates in the Philippines, particularly in Metro Manila, the
Philippine News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Alino took oath as chief of the Philippine National Police
(PNP) together with 14 other newly promoted police generals before
President Fidel Ramos in the Presidential Palace Monday night.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, Alino said that he would give top priority
in solving the pestering kidnapping problem that has given the
country a bad image abroad, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The intensified campaign against kidnappers will be
relentlessly pursued as his pet project in 1998, Alino was quoted
as saying, adding that aside from cracking down on kidnappers, the
PNP will also check other heinous crimes on a nationwide scale.
</P>
<P>
The PNP's failure to arrest kidnappings in the past few months
has caught the fire of the public. Former PNP chief Recaredo
Sarmiento was forced to quit from his post earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos has ordered the PNP and other law enforcement
agencies to intensify their drive against kidnapping incidents
through the safe recovery of victims and the capture of
kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least three kidnapping cases are taking
place every week in the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
