<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Tel Aviv Exchange Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The value of foreign
investments on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange (TASE) has fallen 2
billion shekels (570 million U.S. dollars) since June this year,
the Bank of Israel said in a report published today.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that in October alone, the value of foreign
investments in the TASE fell 5 percent to 18.2 billion shekels
(5.2 billion dollars) from 19.2 billion shekels (5.8 billion
dollars) in September.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the drop mainly to the decline in the value of
shares traded on the stock market. This was due to the crisis
which affected all the world's stock exchanges following the
financial upheavals in the capital markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the foreign investors' proportion of
the total shares traded on the TASE fell to 12.6 percent in
October from 12.8 percent in July. But this is still slightly
higher than the proportion in December 1996, which stood at 11.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The report added that the general public held 71.7 percent of
the shares traded on the TASE in October, compared to 71.2
percent in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
