<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Britain Reshaping Its Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Britain, that had been deeply
engrossed in isolating itself from other European nations and some
world organizations, is busy improving its international image by
promoting its influence in Europe and even in the world arena.
</P>
<P>
The remarkable adjustment of the British foreign policy started
in May when the new Labor government came to power after winning a
landslide victory of the general election.
</P>
<P>
The first major action taken by the Labor government was to
mend Britain's fences with its European Union (EU) allies, which
had been battered by the non-cooperation policy pursued by the
previous Conservative government.
</P>
<P>
Only days after his assumption of office, British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook pledged in a statement "to seize the
opportunity to shape the direction of Europe and make the United
Kingdom a leading player in Europe."
</P>
<P>
To match warm words with actions, British Prime Minister Tony
Blair visited some major EU countries and announced to sign the
EU's "Social Chapter," which showed his determination to break
away from the Conservative's opt-out policy.
</P>
<P>
Despite ruling out Britain's first-wave membership of the
European Monetary Union (EMU), the Blair government sang a
positive tune by saying it would constructively use Britain's EU
rotating presidency next year to strive to make the single
European currency a success.
</P>
<P>
Political commentators said that the "charm offensive" launched
by the Labor government has not only transformed to some extent
the UK-EU confrontation into cooperation but enhanced Britain's
efforts to push the European integration process forward in the
UK-favored direction.
</P>
<P>
Apart from working hard in Europe, the Blair government is set
to reinforce Britain's international status. Addressing the annual
banquet of Lord Mayor of London last month, Blair vowed to make
Britain "pivot of this new world."
</P>
<P>
"With our historic alliances, we can be pivot. We can be
powerful in our influence and make British influence in the world
felt," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Britain took steps in resuming its seat at some
international organizations, such as the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) and the
Pacific Community, in a bid to promote its influence in the whole
world.
</P>
<P>
Britain revoked a previous Conservative government's decision
to withdraw from the United Nations Industrial Development
Organization.
</P>
<P>
Hosting the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in
Edinburgh in October, Britain made painstaking efforts to
revitalize the Commonwealth, hoping to play a leading role in the
54-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government also attached great importance to its
relations with countries in Asia-Pacific, the most economically
dynamic region in the next century, especially the UK-China ties.
</P>
<P>
The smooth handover of Hong Hong on July 1 paved the way for
enhancing Sino-British relations. Foreign Secretary Robin Cook has
reaffirmed that Hong Kong should be "a bridge" rather than a
barrier in the development of UK-China relations.
</P>
<P>
Britain's new Ambassador to China Anthony Galsworthy told
Xinhua that the successful handover of Hong Kong has provided "a
real good opportunity" to promote Sino-British relations.
</P>
<P>
Cook's visits to Malaysia, Singapore, Indonesia, the
Philippines, India and Pakistan this year further intensified
Britain's efforts to gain economic interests in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Britain surely does not forget to forge closer links
with its traditional ally, the United States, which is another
priority in its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Within one month of Blair's election victory, U.S. President
Bill Clinton visited London and became the first foreign leader to
address the Downing Street Cabinet in the past 28 years.
</P>
<P>
During the stand-off between the United Nations and Iraq over
weapon inspection, London was the only staunch American ally in
taking a non-concession tough line.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts here believe that the Labor government,
having made an impressive start in its foreign policy adjustment,
would inevitably meet a number of challenges, particularly in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
It is likely that Britain would fail to achieve its ambition to
become a leading player in the EU mainly due to its decision not
to join the EMU in five years, which is a key project in the
development of the EU in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
And, Britain's future influence and status in Europe as well as
in the world will mainly depend on what kind of role it can play
in the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0171 </DOCNO>
