<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Moves to Modernize in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIANYUNGANG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The northern part of east
China's Jiangsu Province has developed its modern agriculture
rapidly by exploiting agricultural resources and developing
international markets.
</P>
<P>
Experts cited the area's modern agriculture as a major driving
force in promoting development of the local economy. The
industrial output of rural enterprises has stood at more than 20
percent of the provincial total, according to local statistics.
</P>
<P>
The area -- including the five cities of Xuzhou, Lianyungang,
Huaiyin, Yancheng and Suqian -- has set up approximately 1,000
agricultural enterprises, each involving more than 10 million yuan
(1.25 million U.S. dollars) in annual sales. Of these enterprises,
more than 100 have annual sales of 50 million yuan (6.25 million
U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Tapping its abundant agricultural resources, the cities have
set up large centers for planting and processing vegetables,
aquatic products, starch, cotton, grain and wood.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, agricultural centers have been built and extended to
the country's 16 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some 500 joint ventures, cooperative enterprises
and wholely overseas-funded companies have been set up in the area
to exploit agricultural resources and process farm and sideline
products. They have used more than 200 million U.S. dollars in
overseas investment and forged cooperative ties with large-size
agricultural enterprises in the United States, the Republic of
Korea (ROK), Japan and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Exports of farm and sideline products have made up over 60
percent of the area's total exports in recent years. And the
area's vegetables and chickens are sold in over 40 countries and
regions around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Policies Key to Good Harvest of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China's grain output this year
will be about the same as in 1996 and cotton output will exceed
last year's level, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Farmer's per-capita net income will rise, after allowing for
inflation, by four percent over 1996's 1,926 yuan (232 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Many reasons have contributed to the achievements, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
First, the central government has always put agriculture,
especially grain production, at the top of its agenda.
</P>
<P>
At the Central Economic Conference held early this month,
agriculture was ranked as the key factor for maintaining the
economic momentum of "high growth with low inflation".
</P>
<P>
To ensure a rise in farmers' income after the bumper summer
harvest of nearly 124 million tons, the central government fixed a
protective grain purchasing price higher than the price offered by
private grain traders.
</P>
<P>
A special risk fund for grain purchase was established to
allocate adequate funds to State grain reserve centers.
</P>
<P>
Grain reserve centers were required to purchase all the grain
farmers wanted to sell. No purchasing prices below the protective
price would be allowed.
</P>
<P>
Second, a huge investment in agriculture infrastructure has
guaranteed a good harvest. This year, farmers have experienced the
most serious drought since 1970. The water shortage has plagued
most areas north of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources said the drought affected more
than 33 million hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the drought, the central government invested 32.2
billion yuan (3.9 billion US dollars) in irrigation networks and
other agro-facilities. Without the investment, the paper said, it
would be very hard to maintain the present level of crop harvests.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology are the third factor accounting for good
crops. The Seeds Project -- a campaign to cultivate, process and
sow selected excellent strains on a uniform basis -- was launched
nationwide in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Agrotechnical stations at all levels have also helped
increase the contribution of science and technology to higher
grain output by popularizing simple and practical farming
techniques among farmers.
</P>
<P>
Finally, agro-industrialization has made a remarkable
contribution to agricultural development. Township-owned
enterprises have acted as the leading force in the process of
agro-industrialization.
</P>
<P>
Although China has witnessed three successive years of good
harvests, there is no solid basis for the conclusion that China's
grain problem has been solved once and for all, the paper pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
The growth in China's grain output is held back by "the
bottleneck of backward agro-techniques" and "the lack of a sound
grain distribution system," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, limited storage facilities and transportation
capacity will eventually limit the amount of reserves, it added.
</P>
<P>
How to stimulate farmers' incentive to produce and sell more
grain is an important quandary for policy-makers, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
