<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Grows 8.8 Percent (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese industry is estimated to have an added
value of 3,175.2 billion yuan this year, an increase of 11.2
percent. The State-run industry is estimated to grow 5.5 percent,
roughly the same level as last year's.
</P>
<P>
During the January-November period, China's 370,000 industrial
enterprises reaped a profit of 135.6 billion yuan, up 19.6 percent
from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the profit of the State-run enterprises was 34.2
billion yuan, up 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that China's fixed asset investment has
grown steadily. China's fixed asset investment is expected to be
at 2,530 billion yuan in 1997, a nine-percent increase compared
with 1996.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates put China's retails sales of consumer
goods at 2,720 billion yuan in 1997, rising by 11.6 percent, or
10.7 percent when inflation is deducted, over last year.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that China's foreign trade has maintained a
steady growth in 1997, with the total import and export volume
estimated at 320 billion US dollars, an increase of 10
percent over last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Grows 8.8 Percent (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that China is expected to enjoy a trade surplus of 40
billion US dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He added that China is expected to use 62 billion US
dollars of foreign investment in 1997, up 13 percent from that
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The official said that by the end of 1997, China's total
foreign exchange reserves will reach 140 billion US dollars, 35
billion US dollars more than that at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that per-capita income of the urban people in China
is estimated at 5,140 yuan in 1997, an increase of 2.9
percent. Meanwhile, net income of the rural residents
stands at 2,080 yuan, a real growth of four percent.
</P>
<P>
Although China's overall economic situation has scored marked
improvement in 1997, "there are still some problems, which have
aroused the government's keen attention," Ye said. These problems
include a weak agricultural basis, an irrational economic
structure, some enterprises deeply-mired in debts and losses, and
a large number of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
However, looking ahead toward 1998, Ye is optimistic. He
expressed his belief that the Chinese economy will maintain a
high-economic growth and low-inflation scenario. 
</P>
</TEXT>
