<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Develops World's 1st Prawn Gene Map: CSIRO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Australia's top
government-funded research body announced Tuesday it had developed
the world's first prawn gene map as the first step in helping
prawn farmers produce bigger and faster growing prawns.
</P>
<P>
The genetic linkage map, the first for any crustacean species,
will be used by researchers to identify the genes for traits
including growth rate, flesh quality and disease resistance.
</P>
<P>
"Using the map as a guide, large increases in the rate of
genetic improvement of farmed prawns are possible, compared with
those which can be made using traditional breeding strategies,"
the Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization
(CSIRO) said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The early research by a team in Brisbane, capital of Queensland
state, was also designed to estimate the heritability of traits.
</P>
<P>
The success has prompted plans for CSIRO scientists to
collaborate with peers from the Australian Institute of Marine
Science to produce an international genetic linkage map for the
black tiger prawn in research also involving Thailand, China and
the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Pollution Being Curbed in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Beijing cleared up tons of
polystyrene food trays, plastic bags and other disposable cups and
boxes over the weekend with the help of some 300,000 volunteers
from across the capital.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 waste plastic bags and polystyrene trays were
collected by participants and the rubbish on an area of 50,000
square meters combed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The activity is part of this year's large-scale battle against
"white pollution" in the capital. Last Friday of every month is
set by the municipal government as City Clearance Day.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the practice," said a Beijing Environmental
Sanitation Bureau official. The battle against white pollution has
been a focus of the City Clearance activity in the past three
months and will still be so in the near future, the official added.
</P>
<P>
From the new year, plastic bags thinner than 0.015 millimeters
will be banned from the capital's market, and it is suggested that
people use home-made cloth bags instead of plastic ones.
</P>
<P>
Starting last June, six pilot companies have been operating in
the capital to retrieve polystyrene trays. It is estimated that by
the end of the year, 30 percent of the used trays will have been
retrieved and sent for recycling.
</P>
<P>
The environmental sanitation official said: "This is a good way
to curb pollution as well as to investigate the possibility of
recycling resources." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 37 More Kenyans Killed by Unknown Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A total of 37 Kenyans died of
an unknown disease in the past 24 hours in Wajir District,
bringing the death toll to more than 250 in the Northeastern
Province this month.
</P>
<P>
The disease, earlier diagnosed by experts as severe malaria,
is also wiping out thousands of livestock, including camels,
goats and sheep, in the province, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen of the deaths were in the worst-hit Sarif area where
nearly all the villagers were suffering from the disease, said a
provincial medical officer, Abdi Hassan, who just wound up a tour
to the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
A few victims who took anti-malaria and antibiotics recovered,
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the true identity and nature of the epidemic remains
a mystery. The victims diarrhoea, vomit and eventually bleed to
death.
</P>
<P>
Anthrax and yellow fever are also suspected to be the cause of
the death, the World Health Organization said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers are testing samples in laboratories to establish
the cause of the deaths, but the results are not yet known, said
the Geneva-based group.
</P>
<P>
However, initial tests ruled out Ebola fever. Ebola, which
leads to similar symptoms and kills through massive internal
haemorrhaging, was first identified in Sudan in 1970s.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Dr Paul Ndung'u, a veterinarian, attributed the
outbreak to sharing of water sources by people and livestock.
</P>
<P>
He said investigations conducted at the Karatina Veterinary
Investigations Laboratories indicated that the disease was caused
by pasteuvella organisms as a result of months of heavy rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The sick animals were responding positively to sulphadimine
and anti-histamines treatment, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
