<HEADLINE> Foreign Doctors Allowed to Work in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh government has
decided to allow foreign doctors to work in private hospitals and
foreign investors to set up hospitals in the country under joint
venture, according to a press report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign doctors will be given registration with the Bangladesh
Medical and Dental Council for a "limited period" to work in
hospitals, but they will not be allowed to do private practice,
the report quoted Health Ministry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of foreign and local doctors will be decided by the
authorities of the hospitals, the sources said, adding that the
ratio may be 1:3. Any such hospital under the joint venture would
be of at least 250 beds.
</P>
<P>
"We have been considering foreign investment in the health
sector to provide improved healthcare services and transfer of
technology," said Health Secretary Mhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry in November this year made a proposal in
this regard and it is now awaiting final approval from the Board
of Investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
