<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM on Russian-U.S. Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States is the sole
superpower in the world Monday but that does not mean that the
world is a U.S.-dominated monopolar world, Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the Cold War period, the United States provided nuclear
umbrella for the west but in the world today that protection is no
longer needed. So it is wrong to confuse the concept of superpower
with that of the monopolar, Primakov said in an interview with the
Russian newspaper Independent.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there remained differences between Russia and
the United States over issues in the Middle East. He said he hoped
the United States would adopt a more realistic attitude when
discussing those issues.
</P>
<P>
Primakov also denied that Russia has offered missile technology
to Iran, saying such a claim was made by the pro-Israel lobbies in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
He also said that some people in the United States were getting
angry when U.S. domination over the Middle East was broken by
other countries.
</P>
<P>
As for the application of the Baltic countries -- Lativia,
Estonia and Lithuania -- for membership of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), Primakov indicated Russia would not
make any concessions over the issue.
</P>
<P>
If the three countries are accepted by NATO as new members,
Russia will re-consider its relations with the military alliance,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that he believed the Baltic countries should stay
neutral, which could guarantee their safety, rather than joining
NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Helps India Develop Micro-Hydel Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A chain of small hydel units
is being set up in India's hills under a United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) scheme to wean the local communities
away from their dependence on forest resources for energy needs,
the local economic newspaper Business Standard said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The local people's dependence on forest resources for energy
needs has proved to be a major cause for deforestation and
ecological damage.
</P>
<P>
Around 20 units are proposed to be set up under the scheme, to
be funded by the Global Environment Facility (GEF) which has
provided 25 million US dollars for the purpose. The scheme is
expected to be completed by 1999.
</P>
<P>
The project attains significance in view of the continued
resistance of the inhabitants to big dams, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
