<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Buoyed by Aid Agreement for S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices rose Tuesday,
the final trading day for the year, with the key Nikkei index
recovering to the 15,000 mark in response to an international
agreement on ways to ease South Korean firms' large external debts.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 483.52 points, or 3.27 percent,
from Monday's close to 15,258.74.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, gained 27.16 points, or 2.37 percent,
going to 1,175.03.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section rose to an estimated 180 million
shares from Monday morning's 170 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo market has no afternoon session Tuesday and its
trading will be resumed January 5.
</P>
<P>
The market was quiet throughout the day with most investors
away for year-end holidays, traders said.
</P>
<P>
At the outset, the robust share prices on Wall Street and
Chicago led the Nikkei index above the 15,000 line.
</P>
<P>
The news about aid by major international commercial banks to
South Korea further buoyed market sentiment, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,327 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outpaced losers 921 to 176 with 138 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
