<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavian Economy Improves in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The national economy of the
Yugoslav Federal Republic picked up in 1997 despite lack of
working funds and foreign financial support, a top statistician
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Milovan Zivkovic, director of the country's Statistics Bureau,
told reporters that gross social output of 1997 rose 7.4 percent
over that of the previous year, with industrial and agricultural
outputs going up by 9.6 percent and five percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia also managed to maintain the stability of commodity
prices and the exchange rate of its currency, the Dinar, and
thereby effectively harnessed inflation.
</P>
<P>
December prices were only 9.6 percent higher than the same
month of the previous year, the lowest price increase in 15 years
except for 1994.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the economy, people's living standards
also grew in real terms. Average monthly wages increased 21.5
percent to 806 Dinars (about 137.5 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Yugoslavia's per capita national income was 1,550
dollars, up from 1,250 dollars three years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Zivkovic said, it would take seven to eight years for
the country's per capita national income to return to the 1989
level of 2,850 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Adopts New Tariffs for Next 3 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Presidential
Palace has agreed the adoption of new tariff rates for imported
oil and petrochemical products for the next three years, local
press reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said a uniform duty of 3 percent would be imposed
on both crude and refined oil imports. The country's Supreme Court
earlier ruled "unconstitutional" a law levying a 3-percent tariff
on crude and 7 percent on refined oil products.
</P>
<P>
The uniform tariff will be retroactive to December 19.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Palace sources said the new rates would be
implemented even without the legislature's endorsement through an
executive order during the Congress' break in the coming holidays.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the oil tariffs, the Palace also approved a
7-percent duty on completely knocked down parts of cars and a
40-percent tariff on buildup units. The former will be raised to
10 percent by 1999 as the latter cut to 30 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
For petrochemical products, the reports said, the Palace
approved the imposition of a 10-percent duty on petrochemical
products and zero to 3 percent for monomers.
</P>
<P>
This means that local petrochemical producers will have to
improve their competitiveness to compete with petrochemical
imports. Industry players have not given up their opposition to
this new tariffs and have vowed to lobby further.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Palace also agreed to abolish duties on
many information technology products to comply with the country's
early commitment to the World Trade Organization, the reports
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees 1st Current Account Surplus in 14 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Thailand registered in October
its first current account surplus in 14 years, indicating hopes of
a turnaround in the economy, according to the Bangkok Post
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus for October is estimated at around
500 million US dollars, the newspaper quotes Olarn Chaipravat,
chairman of the Thai Bankers' Association, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Olarn believed that in the last three months of the year, the
country could have a total surplus of about 2 billion dollars, a
strong positive sign for the overall economy.
</P>
<P>
The surplus shows that foreign exchange inflows from Thai
exports are higher than capital outflows for payments on imports
and foreign debt, signaling that monthly cashflow is beginning to
show a surplus after years of being in the red.
</P>
<P>
The cash outflow was reduced as a result of the rollover of
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
However, Olarn warned, "we have already passed this year. But
we still have a heavy burden for next year."  
</P>
</TEXT>
