<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Nigeria to Sign Gas Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Italy's national electricity
board, Enel, and the Nigerian Liquefied Natural Gas company will
sign an agreement Wednesday to sort out a gas supply dispute, Enel
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the two sides said the final agreement for the
supply of 3.5 billion cubic meters of liquefied Nigerian natural
gas starting in the fall of 1999 was based on preliminary set in
September.
</P>
<P>
Difficulties arose when Enel's attempts to build
regassification plant at Montalto di Castro on the coast near Rome
and at Monfalcone ran aground because of protests from grass-roots
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
The plants were needed for the Nigerian gas to be turned back
into the gaseous state for introduction into the national gas
grid. Failure to build them meant there was nowhere for the
Nigerian gas to go and could have meant Enel having to pay over
11.75 billion dollars under its 20-year take-or-pay contract with
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The compromise solution involves unloading the liquefied gas in
France where it will be regassified by Gaz de France under an
agreement signed a few days ago. Swap agreements between Enel and
Gas de France will bring an equivalent amount of gas to Italy
through an Italian terminal in the Austro-Slovakian border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
