<HEADLINE> Political Stability the Key, Says Fiat Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Political stability is the key to
Italy's economic development, says Cesare Romiti, chairman of the
country's largest auto maker, Fiat.
</P>
<P>
Romiti says this to the latest issue of the economic monthly,
Gente Money, which will be on newsstands on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Until Italy solves the problem of political stability, it
cannot get on with the structural reforms needed to re-launch the
economy, Romiti said. Political stability is the number one item
for both Italy and Europe in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The watchwords for Italians in 1998 are "confidence and
courage", Romiti said. He elaborated: the Italians should have
"confidence in one's own abilities which are extraordinary and for
which all the world envies us", and the courage "to change" rather
than hanging on to the present. 
</P>
