<HEADLINE> Poultry Giant Docked $6 Million for Illegal Gifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Poultry giant Tyson Foods
Inc. agreed to pay six million U.S. dollars in fines and costs
after pleading guilty Monday to a federal charge it made illegal
gifts to former Agriculture Secretary, Mike Espy.
</P>
<P>
The Arkansas-based company was accused of providing Espy and
others with football tickets, presidential inaugural ball tickets,
lodgings and other gifts.
</P>
<P>
Espy was indicted in August on charges he accepted gratuities
from Tyson and other agribusiness firms. Espy has denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
The Tyson agreement must still be approved by United States
District Judge Ricardo Urbina, who scheduled sentencing for
January 14, Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
As part of the plea bargaining, the company must institute
ethics training and other safeguards against future wrongdoing,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Espy and former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros are the
highest-ranking officials of the Clinton administration to be
accused of a crime.
</P>
<P>
Cisneros was indicted this month on conspiracy, obstructing
justice and other charges related to false statements to the FBI
about payments to his former mistress. 
</P>
