<HEADLINE> Ex-Bank Indonesia Directors Charged with Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Police investigators
officially charged three of the four dismissed Bank Indonesia
directors with corruption Monday, and imposed an indefinite
overseas travel ban on them, Indonesian Police Chief Dibyo Widodo
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports today quoted him as saying that the three
-- Hendrobudiyanto, Paul Soetopo and Heru Soepraptomo -- were
undergoing intensive investigation on suspicion of corruption
involving a total of 1.5 trillion rupiah (300 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hendrobudiyanto was director of private foreign exchange
supervision of the central bank, Soetopo was director of market
operations and Heru was director of legal affairs. The fourth man,
who was also dismissed from his post, Mansjurdin Nurdin was
director of supervision for private non-foreign exchange banks.
</P>
<P>
The removal came at the peak of the monetary crisis in the
country which has seen the rupiah plunge from 2,400 to the dollar
in June to as low as 6,000 rupiah per dollar last week.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta Police Chief Maj. Gen. Hamami Nata said Monday the
former bank executives were being questioned for their alleged
involvement in corrupt acts in connection with loans extended to
several ailing private banks.
</P>
<P>
He refused to provide further details about the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
