<HEADLINE> Defense Major Cost in Yugoslav Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslavia's Chamber of
Citizens of the Federal Assembly (Lower House) approved the 1998
budget put forward by the government Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The total budget for 1998 is set at 9.693 billion dinars (about
1.64 billion U.S. dollars), up 4.9 percent over this year's
budget, said the Yugoslav Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
The budget will account for 9.13 percent of the country's total
"social product" -- the equivalent of the Gross National Product
-- next year, which is estimated to reach 106.17 billion dinars
(about 18 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The greatest expenditure in the budget is defense, which
amounts to 6.5 billion dinars (about 1.11 billion dollars),
accounting for 67.6 percent in the aggregate budget.
</P>
<P>
The second greatest is the administrative spending, which makes
up 13.6 percent of the budget, followed by disabled armymen's
pensions, making up 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's government budget comes mainly from commercial
goods taxes and duty tax, which are respectively 5.2 billion
dinars (about 887 million dollars) and three billion dinars (about
512 million dollars). 
</P>
