<HEADLINE> China's Trade Surplus Hits 40 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade has
maintained a steady growth in 1997, with the total import and
export volume estimated at 320 billion US dollars, an increase of
10 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Ye Zhen, spokesman for the State
Statistics Bureau, at a press conference here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Ye said China's trade surplus in 1997 is expected to reach 40
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said overseas capital has continued to flow into China.
The overseas capital actually used this year is expected
to reach 62 billion US dollars, up 13 percent from last
year. The distribution of overseas capital has been further
rationalized.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign currency reserves has maintained constant
increases, he said, adding that by the end of 1997 total foreign
currency reserves will reach 140 billion US dollars, some 35
billion US dollars more than that at the beginning of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
