<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Machine Tools Imports Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Imports of machine tools
declined sharply this year, the first time in the past three
years, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Customs figures show the imports of metal-processing machine
tools hit 1.18 billion U.S. dollars by the end of November, down
35.4 percent from the same period last year. Machine tools exports
reached 253 million, up 12.8 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
"The cancellation of favorable tariff treatments on equipment
imported by foreign-funded ventures is one of the major reasons
for the drastic drop in imports, equal to about 648 million
U.S. dollars." Said Zheng Guowei, a member of the Science and
Technology Committee under the Ministry of Machine-Building
Industry.
</P>
<P>
The import tariff plus value-added tax on machine tools now
range from 25 percent to 40 percent of the actual value of the
equipment since the central government announced the restoration
of the tariffs on capital goods imported by foreign-invested
enterprises and some technical renovation projects.
</P>
<P>
Lower demand, primarily caused by the tight credit policy of
the central government, also contributed to the slump in imports
of machine tools, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
However, the future state of the industry would depend on the
extent of the tax breaks and exemptions the central government
plans for 1998.
</P>
<P>
A reliable source said, in a bid to encourage foreign direct
investment, China is to resume a favourable import tariff and tax
treatment for both foreign-funded ventures and State enterprises,
starting next year.
</P>
<P>
The market share of the State-owned machine tool manufacturers
is expected to expand due to the government's preferential scheme
to extend loans and to enterprises' increasing concentration on
quality improvement, product development and after-sales service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Unemployment Down in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's unemployment rate
reduced to 5.35 percent in November from the previous month's 5.71
percent, the Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The November fall was due to temporary hiring, the institute
said.
</P>
<P>
From January to November, 395 Brazilian companies were sold or
merged, 1.3 percent more compared with the same period last
year. That might be translated into a decline in the number of
jobs available, the institute said. 
</P>
