<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Huaihe River Emerges As Important Grain Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The northern area of the
Huaihe River, an emerging grain production center in east China's
Jiangsu Province, has played an increasingly important role in
boosting the province's grain production.
</P>
<P>
The area is part of the Huanghuaihai Plain created by the
Yellow River, China's second largest, the Huaihe River and the
Haihe River.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the area is expected to increase grain
production by 3.2 percent to 18.75 billion kilograms this year,
580 million kilograms more than the 1996 figure. The 1997 grain
output should account for 51 percent of the province's total
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The area, including 28 counties in northern Jiangsu, has
greatly improved its basic farming conditions and grain output
since the project to promote the all-around development of
agriculture was started 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
During the past 10 years, the area has invested 3.12 billion
yuan (390 million U.S. dollars) in building water conservation
facilities, transforming more than one million hectares of low-
and medium-yield fields and increasing irrigated land by 287,000
hectares.
</P>
<P>
To produce more high-yield farm products, the area introduced
improved varieties and new agricultural production technologies.
In the Huanghuaihai Plain, more than 95 percent of wheat is of
improved varieties. Statistics show that wheat output in some
counties and towns has exceeded 7,500 kilograms per
hectare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
