<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil To Push Anti-AIDS Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Health Ministry of Brazil
has invited 20,000 national companies to develop during 1998 a
series of programs aimed at containing AIDS inside their facilities.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said on Monday that so far 12,000 companies have
accepted the proposal and next year they will receive written and
video-taped information about the disease.
</P>
<P>
The program is based on an investigation carried out by the
Social Service of Industries of Brazil (SSIB) and with the support
of the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that out of 116,389 people infected with HIV
in Brazil --in official figures--, more than 80 percent are
between 15 and 45 years old.
</P>
<P>
The investigation shows that 96.4 percent of the people
interviewed agreed with the measures of "safe sex".
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government is trying to carry out a prevention
program among workers, and the main move is the fostering of the
usage of condoms, in men and in women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
