<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Indonesia Increases in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The value of foreign
investment approved by the Indonesian government rose 13 percent
to 33.8 billion U.S. dollars this year, State Minister of
Investment Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the number of projects approved for
foreign investors this year declined by 11.4 percent to 790.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the value of domestic investment approvals
also increased by 19.1 percent to 119.9 trillion rupiah (one U.S.
dollar equals 5,000 rupiah at present).
</P>
<P>
The minister said the chemical industry remained the most
attractive sector to foreign investors this year, with approvals
in the sector totaling 93 projects worth 12.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Transportation followed with 36 projects approvals totaling 5.9
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sanyoto said foreign investment approvals for export-oriented
projects grew 17.3 percent to 11.5 billion dollars, with the
number of projects declining to 402 from 520 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said most of this year's foreign investment approvals came
from Britain, which had committed to 31 projects totaling 5.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Britain is followed by Japan, which invested in 94 projects
worth 5.4 billion dollars. Direct investment from Germany totaled
3.5 billion dollars and Malaysia 2.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Indonesia's foreign investment stood at 29.9 billion
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
