<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ASUNCION -- The external debt of Paraguay grew 5.8 percent in
1997 against last year, according to the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Foreign obligations will reach 1.41 billion dollars with a
swelling tendency expected over 1998, it added. The country's
major creditors are multilateral organizations, which have
provided 61 percent of the revenues.
</P>
<P>
Payments of external debt amounted this year to 175.8 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Ministry of Public Works of Panama signed
recently five contracts worth 83 million dollars, for a four-lane
rehabilitation and enlargement of the Pan American highway in the
country.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Production of frog meat in Brazil reached 270 tons
this year, an increment of 35 percent with respect to the 200 tons
last year.
</P>
<P>
The Rio based Society of Frog Growers said that sales of frog
meat hit 3.2 million dollars in 1997, 6.7 percent more than 1996.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is third placed in the production of frog meat, just
after Thailand with an output of 600 tons annually, and Indonesia
with 400 tons.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile is closing 1997 with a consumption of 1.73
million tons of steel, 5 percent over the demand in 1996.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of Aza steel manufacturer, Von Muhlenbrock,
explained that the increment is due to the dynamism showed by
mining, manufacturing and construction sectors. Such industries
grew 11.5, 1.3 and 5.2 percent respectively for the year.
</P>
<P>
He said that consumption per capita of steel in Chile reached
146 kilograms 1997. That amount means Chile is the leading Latin
American country in steel production.
</P>
