<HEADLINE> Anand, Adams to Go into Speed Tie-break </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRONINGEN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Viswanathan Anand and
Michael Adams will play a speed chess tie-break after drawing
their fourth match of the World Chess Championship eliminator in
Groningen of the Netherlands on Monday.
</P>
<P>
India's Anand and Adams of England drew all four of their
regular matches here and will face each other on Tuesday in two
matches of 25 minutes plus 10 seconds per move.
</P>
<P>
If there is still a deadlock, two games of 15 minutes plus 10
seconds per move will played.
</P>
<P>
A final "sudden-death" blitz tiebreaker will be fought if that
two games are also not enough to decide the victor, who will
challenge Anatoly Karpov of Russia for the world title in January.
</P>
<P>
The International Chess Federation (FIDE) world championship
will be staged in a six-game format in Lausanne, Switzerland from
January 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
