<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drinking and Driving among Young Drops in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The rate of drinking and
driving among younger drivers fell sharply in the United States
this year, a leading research firm has found.
</P>
<P>
It is now less than one-half the level of 1985, the
Illinois-based Insurance Research Council (IRC) said in a press
release today.
</P>
<P>
A survey based on in-house interviews with 1,966 drivers living
in the United States found that 18 percent of those aged 18-24
reported drinking and driving in 1997, compared to 29 percent in
1990 and 48 percent in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Among drivers aged 25-29 the rate of drinking and driving was
23 percent in 1997, against 36 percent in 1990 and 53 percent in
1985.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that the American public supports tougher
drunk driver penalties.
</P>
<P>
Fifty one percent of respondents believe that the drunk
driver's license should be suspended or revoked when caught in an
accident even if there were no injuries.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of respondents favoring jail time goes up to 28
percent if the accident caused serious injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA: Using Seat Belt Can Prevent Turbulent Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Most of injuries in
incidents of in-flight turbulence can be prevented if passengers
wear their seat belts whenever they are seated, the U.S. Federal
Aviation Administration (FAA) said today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that two passengers were killed and 63
seriously injured in 252 incidents of turbulence reported by major
U.S. air carries operating around the world between 1981 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
An average of 58 passengers are injured each year if minor
injuries are accounted. About 22 flight attendants are also injured
annually in turbulence, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said it has spent half a million U.S. dollars over
the past year on television, radio and print advertisements to
urge travelers to buckle up. But still many ignore the advice.
Even when pilots illuminate fasten seat belt signs, some people
still refuse to wear seat belts.
</P>
<P>
Air turbulence can occur unexpectedly, even when skies look
clear. So the FAA recommends that airline passengers wear seat
belts whenever they are seated, not just when fasten seat belt
signs are turned on.
</P>
<P>
Fasten seat belt signs were reportedly on for less than a
minute before sudden turbulence hit a United Airlines jet flying
between Narita, Japan, and Honolulu Sunday night, killing a woman
and injuring 102 other passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sales of Existing Homes Dip Slightly in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nation-wide sales
of existing homes declined slightly in November, but are finishing
1997 at a record pace, the National Association of Realtors
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 4.38 million units in November. That's just 0.2 percent
lower than October's 4.39 million rate, the highest level since
the group began tracking sales in 1968.
</P>
<P>
The association projected sales for all of 1997 will total 4.31
million units, also the best in 29 years, and forecast 4.09
million units would be sold in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The robust home sales have been enhanced by low mortgage rates
and strong economic growth, which pushed the nation's unemployment
rate to a 24-year low of 4.6 percent in November and produced the
strongest income growth in eight years.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged 7.21 percent in
November, the lowest in 21 months. They fell to about 7.1 percent
this month as some investors fled Asian financial chaos for the
safety of U.S. government securities.
</P>
<P>
The strong sales this year are giving homeowners a dividend.
Home values are appreciating three times faster than the overall
inflation rate of about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The median price of an existing home was 124,400 U.S. dollars
in November, up 6 percent from a year ago. By region, sales fell
2.7 percent in the Midwest to a seasonally adjusted 1.09 million
units in November and 1.6 percent in the Northeast to a rate of
630,000 units. Sales were unchanged in the West at a rate of
990,000 units. They rose 1.8 percent in the South to 1.67 million
units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Rally on Firm Markets Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in Europe
all surged strongly and ended sharply higher today, boosted by
firm stock markets worldwide on general optimism over the economy
of the crisis-hit South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index breached the 5,100-point level on the
back of an impressive rally in New York and ended 1.96 percent or
98.5 points higher at 5,112.4.
</P>
<P>
But volumes were typically low as investors drifted back to the
market after the Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that takeover speculation boosted stocks in the
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt also closed higher although dealers
said trading was extremely thin.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index rose by 1.83 percent, or 75.58 points, to
4,197.37 by the end of the session.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French shares forged ahead and finished up in
response to Wall Street strength and hopes for Asian markets, with
the CAC-40 index finishing the session 68.19 points higher at
2,939.46. 
</P>
</TEXT>
