<HEADLINE> UN Chief to Approve Iraqi Oil-for-Food Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of
the United Nations Kofi Annan would approve an Iraqi food and
medical distribution plan this week, UN spokesman Fred Eckhard
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Eckhard said the Iraqi Government
submitted the plan on Saturday to the UN representative in
Baghdad, and the papers are being forwarded to the UN Headquarters
in New York.
</P>
<P>
"We would hope that the package could be approved by the end of
this week," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the UN Resolution 986, which was adopted in
1995, Iraq can sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six
months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for
its people. The so-called oil-for-food plan is aimed to relief
effects of the sanctions imposed on Iraq after it invaded Kuwait
1990.
</P>
<P>
The plan began last December and was renewed by the Security
Council of the United Nations on December 4.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq suspended oil exports on December 5 to protest delays
in receiving food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies. Iraq
said it would resume oil exports once Annan approves the current
six-month plan  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
