<DOCNO> XIE19971230.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Watches Closely Trans-Iranian Pipeline Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States could not
impose sanctions on Turkmenistan for its new gas pipeline to Iran,
but it would be looking closely at any feasibility studies for a
proposed pipeline from Turkmenistan to Turkey via Iran, the State
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said the Iran-Libya
Sanctions Act (ILSA), signed by President Bill Clinton in 1996 to
impose sanctions on any companies investing more than 20 million
dollars in either Iran's or Libya's energy sections, could not be
imposed on the gas pipeline between Turkmenistan and Iran,
inaugurated today, because the construction of the pipeline
predated the act.
</P>
<P>
"It doesn't trigger it," Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But the United States would not let off any other project of
trans-Iranian pipelines without scrutiny of their possible
violation of the U.S. law, Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"We will examine carefully any new proposals for the
construction of trans-Iranian pipelines in light of the provisions
of ILSA. If any such project is found to involve sanctionable
activity, we will take appropriate action under the law," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United States knew a feasibility study for the
proposed pipeline from Turkmenistan to Turkey via Iran was about
to go ahead after the three countries on Sunday gave the authority
to the Anglo-Dutch oil company Royal Dutch-Shell for that work.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States would "withhold judgment and see what
actually was involved if it moved to the stage of execution."
</P>
<P>
"The United States opposes as a matter of policy the
construction of pipelines across Iran," he said, explaining why
Washington would monitor the progress of the proposed
trans-Iranian pipeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
