<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Renews Call for Peacekeepers in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat today renewed a call for deploying international
peacekeepers in the West Bank to secure peace between Israel and
the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
According to Palestinian Radio today, Arafat said in Gaza that
under Israeli-Palestinian peace accords, international
peacekeeping forces should be deployed in the area, like those now
stationed in the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Arafat raised the proposal when meeting with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in London on December 18. The Palestinian
National Authority on Saturday ratified this idea.
</P>
<P>
Arafat would set forth the proposal as part of his
comprehensive plan on the final settlement with the Israelis
during his coming talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton next
month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu are to
meet separately with Clinton, who tries to mediate by himself in
an effort to advance the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has rejected Arafat's demand. Netanyahu's adviser
David Bar-Illan said Arafat's call was nothing new, and Israel
would not accept it.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Israel's rejection of his proposal, Arafat
reminded that "Israel may not keep wide tracts of the West Bank,
they must remember the agreements they signed."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is debating the establishment of two
security zones along the Jordan River and 1949 armistice line,
which will be controlled by Israeli troops, to ensure its security
after the final settlement is reached with the Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
